\section*{Introduction to CompTIA A+}
\label{sec:org158f168}
\subsection*{This the A+}
\label{sec:org642142b}

\begin{itemize}
\item The Computing Technology Industry Association (CompTIA) is a non-profit trade association which issues professional certifications for the information technology industry.  The A+ is one of the first of these certifications, and is intended to encompass the practical and useful information that anyone working in the IT industry should know.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Parts of the A+}
\label{sec:org74444f0}

\begin{itemize}
\item The A+ is in two parts: 1001 and 1002.  Each test is 90 minutes long and they can be taken the same day or on different days - most people take them separately so that they can prepare for each test on its own terms.  Here is the approximate breakdown of material covered on the A+ 1001:
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{a table of the parts}
\label{sec:orga424de8}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
Domain & Percentage of examination\\
\hline
1.0 Mobile Devices & 14\%\\
2.0 Networking & 20\%\\
3.0 Hardware & 27\%\\
4.0 Virtualization and Cloud Computing & 12\%\\
5.0 Hardware and Network Troubleshooting & 27\%\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Types of questions}
\label{sec:org74165af}

Both exams will consist of a mixture of traditional multiple choice questions and a differently-formatted type of exercises called Performance Based Questions (PBQs).  We will prepare you for both types of questions.  The following notes are organized based on the exact areas in which CompTIA expects you to have knowledge.

\section*{1.1 – Given a scenario, install and configure laptop hardware and components.}
\label{sec:orgfe12620}

\subsection*{Hardware/device replacement}
\label{sec:org88849ee}
\begin{itemize}
\item In general, the features that make laptops so useful and desirable - small size, light weight, ability to operate free of wired environments - can combine to make these devices more difficult, overall, to repair.

\item To occupy the least volume in the case of the laptop, components are often specially designed, interlocked tightly with each other, and in some cases, covered with glue or epoxy.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{That said,}
\label{sec:orge153a6d}
\begin{itemize}
\item individual components of laptops can be repaired under the right circumstances
\item Many laptops have a modular design that eases the removal and replacement of different parts.  This is particularly true of random access memory (RAM) and hard drives.

\item But a number of laptops will not be able to have anything upgraded or repaired by the user.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Precautions when repairing a laptop}
\label{sec:org52fa185}
\begin{itemize}
\item It is important to remember, before repairing \textbf{any} electronic device, that the device is powered off and its power cable removed.
\item In most situations it will be important to use anti-static precautions such as an anti-static band or mat (pictured).  This will wick away some of your own electric charge and prevent that charge from damaging components of the device.
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Antistatic pad}
\label{sec:org095936b}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{./images/1-1AntiStaticPad.jpeg}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Laptop Keyboards}
\label{sec:org4466696}
\begin{itemize}
\item Often the number of keys is sacrificed for space and weight
\item More function keys and combination keys than seen on desktop keyboards
\item Smaller than most desktop keyboards
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Function / special keys}
\label{sec:org0ec50ae}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{./images/1-1keyboardFunctionKeys.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Keyboard function keys, activated by pressing the Fn key}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item Important keys are concealed in the function keys on the average laptop computer
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Function / special keys, cont}
\label{sec:org773467c}
\begin{itemize}
\item these include: 
\begin{itemize}
\item volume settings
\item toggling between the internal monitor or an external one
\item turning on or off the wireless signal
\item controlling the brightness of the screen.
\end{itemize}
\item These buttons are usually activated by pressing the \textbf{Fn} key in combination with them.
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Some users do not understand the nature of the function keys and may activate them without realizing.
\begin{itemize}
\item An important thing to check, for example, if a computer's wireless connection does not seem to be working, is whether it might have been inadvertantly turned off by the user.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Keyboard backlight}
\label{sec:org8fca72c}
\begin{itemize}
\item Many keyboards are backlit with small LEDs to enable their use in the dark or in dim light
\begin{itemize}
\item This feature is usually controlled by a function key or in the device preferences through the operating system.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Troubleshooting laptop keyboards}
\label{sec:orga1c8cc6}

\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{./images/1-1KeyboardOutline.jpeg}
\caption{laptop keyboard}
\end{figure}

\begin{itemize}
\item Laptop keyboards can be replaced, but:
\begin{itemize}
\item They are often tightly integrated in the frame of a laptop
\item So this is often difficult or expensive.
\item A non- or poorly functioning keyboard can be due to:
\begin{itemize}
\item dust or dirt accumulating under the keys
\item a broken or twisted data cable under the keyboard.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Hard drives}
\label{sec:orga368f70}
\subsubsection*{SSD vs. hybrid vs. magnetic disk}
\label{sec:org13b52e0}

\begin{itemize}
\item We will discuss this further in Storage Devices, but briefly:
\begin{itemize}
\item Magnetic disks (HDD = Hard Disk Drive):
\begin{itemize}
\item Spinning platters with stylus - slow, consumes power, generally larger and heavier
\item Due to their mechanical and more delicate nature can be damaged or disabled by sudden movement
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{./images/1-1-LaptopHDD.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{a mechanical, magnetic hard drive in all its glory}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item Solid State Drives (SSDs)
\begin{itemize}
\item no moving parts - all flash memory
\item silent, faster than HDD, lighter, more durable, uses less power - all ideal features for laptops
\item more expensive than HDDs, but their price is gradually decreasing
\item 1.8 inch and 2.5 inch form factors
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Hybrid drive (SSHD)
\begin{itemize}
\item Two components: traditional, magnetic hard drive and an SSD.
\item In hybrid drives, the SSD component serves as a cache for the magnetic component, allowing for faster drives.  These will be cheaper than 100\% SSDs but have some of the disadvantages of mechanical drives: weight, power use, vulnerable to kinetic energy
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/1-1-HDD-SSD.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{An HDD (left) and an SSD (right)}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{M.2 drives}
\label{sec:org5552785}
\begin{itemize}
\item Smaller form factor slot for SSDs
\item Can have up to 4 GB/s throughput
\begin{itemize}
\item Highest speeds only with Non-Volatile Memory Express (NVMe)
\item Not all computers have NVMe built in, so older machines will not be able to use the full potential of M.2 drives
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-4-M2drive.png}
\captionof{figure}{M.2 drive}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{1.8in vs. 2.5in}
\label{sec:orge759f51}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{HDDs} in laptops typically 2.5in
\item \textbf{SSDs} can be 1.8 or 2.5 in
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/1-1-18+25Drives.png}
\captionof{figure}{Side-by-side comparison of 1.8in and 2.5in SSDs and HDD}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Hard drive fragmenting / defragmenting}
\label{sec:orgc891d41}
\begin{itemize}
\item We will discuss this more when we discuss memory devices in excruciating detail later on.  
\begin{itemize}
\item Briefly:
\begin{itemize}
\item On an HDD, files are stored in \textbf{clusters}
\begin{itemize}
\item When saving, data is saved to the next vacant cluster, even if not adjacent
\item Over time, files become spread out and take longer to retrieve
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item This problem can be solved through a process called ``defragmentation''
\begin{itemize}
\item The hard drive reorganizes itself so that related information is geographically related as well.
\item Defragmentation can take time and can produce further wear on the drive but at the end of the process the drive will be a bit snappier.
\end{itemize}
\item This is \textbf{not} needed in SSDs - since every piece of the information on an SSD takes the same amount of time to be retrieved, defragmenting these drives will make no difference.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Defragmentation image}
\label{sec:orge231edd}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/1-1-defragmenting.png}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Here's a mechanical hard drive:}
\label{sec:orgc7776e9}
\subsection*{Memory}
\label{sec:org8f33eec}
\begin{itemize}
\item Laptops use smaller memory modules than desktop machines:
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Small Outline Dual In-line Memory Module (SODIMM):
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
Memory Type & Module Format\\
\hline
DDR & 200-pin\\
DDR2 & 200-pin\\
DDR3 & 204-pin\\
DDR4 & 260-pin\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Micro-DIMM: Micro-Dual In-line Memory Module
\begin{itemize}
\item We will be discussing the particulars of memory at much greater length later on, don't worry!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{./images/1-1-SODIMM.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{Here's some SODIMMs!}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Installing SODIMM}
\label{sec:orgeeaddc6}
\begin{itemize}
\item Carefully, following manual!
\begin{itemize}
\item Memory module goes in at 45 degree angle
\item Align notch
\item press down gently until it snaps in
\item Two clips lock into notches on side
\item Put everything back.  Make sure no extra screws.
\begin{itemize}
\item Sometimes, no matter how hard you try it does not seat correctly
\item OS will not see the memory you installed
\item Try re-seating
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}




\subsection*{Portable device storage media}
\label{sec:orgdd3b5a9}
\begin{itemize}
\item Different sizes and capacities of storage media for portable devices
\item SD (Secure Digital) card:
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{./images/1-1SDcardspng.png}
\captionof{figure}{Different sizes of storage cards for portable devices}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Optical drive}
\label{sec:org394ae60}

\begin{itemize}
\item Although this is listed as a CompTIA objective for the laptop section, CD and DVD drives found only in older laptops
\begin{itemize}
\item We will discuss this type of media later in the class.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Wireless cards and Bluetooth modules}
\label{sec:org2d31400}
\begin{itemize}
\item Laptops can have a number of wireless communications interfaces:
\begin{itemize}
\item from 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz WiFi
\item Near field communications (NFC)
\item Bluetooth
\item (we will discuss these a great deal more, presently.)
\item These connections are usually controlled by the operating system
\begin{itemize}
\item Can be changed in the system preferences
\item Some laptops will have function buttons on the keyboard to turn wireless signals on or off.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Cellular card}
\label{sec:orgbcef6ee}
\begin{itemize}
\item Increasingly, laptops have the option to enable a separate cellular data communication.  
\begin{itemize}
\item This is of a type different from more conventional WiFi, but still using radio signals of different frequencies.
\item This service is handled on the backend by the user's cellular provider.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Video card}
\label{sec:org8a6d642}
\begin{itemize}
\item In most cases, the video card (or, the portion of the hardware that handles the translation and display of video signals) is built into the CPU.
\begin{itemize}
\item This is, again, due to the space that this saves.
\item However, this also means that laptops will \textbf{usually} have a less robust ability to display mathematically complex graphics and may struggle with some intensive graphical and video applications.
\end{itemize}
\item Video cards on laptops are usually not upgradable.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{DC jack}
\label{sec:org5cda837}
\begin{itemize}
\item Laptop computers need to convert alternating current (AC) from household electrical sockets to direct current (DC) for the use of most of its internal components.
\begin{itemize}
\item In most latpops, this conversion happens inside the ``power brick'' that we have to lug around.
\begin{itemize}
\item The power conversion unit (``brick'') is designed for particular voltages, or may have a switch on it to convert between 110 volts and 220 volts (the most common global voltage values).
\item Some power adapters can switch between voltage schemes automatically, but others cannot.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{DC jack, cont'd}
\label{sec:orgdc6f5fe}
\begin{itemize}
\item The plug that connects an external power supply to the computer is known as the ``DC jack.''
\begin{itemize}
\item In many cases the plug size and type is unique to a particular computer, and this must be checked carefully if a user is getting a new or repaired power supply.
\item The attached picture shows a ``universal'' power brick and the wide variety of different attachments it needs to be able to attach to different laptops.
\item There is a slow movement to standardize DC jacks; for example, all new Apple Macintosh laptops now use USB-C type connections rather than the older, more unique power cords.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{./images/1-1-DCjacks2.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{A universal laptop power supply}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Troubleshooting power problems}
\label{sec:org422c188}
\begin{itemize}
\item Check the power LED
\item Check connections
\begin{itemize}
\item loose / damaged DC jack?
\end{itemize}
\item Correct power adapter
\item Check battery
\item Check if on \textbf{standby}, \textbf{suspend}, \textbf{hibernate}
\item Check power outlet!
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{High level power troubleshooting}
\label{sec:orgcd39af1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Discharge the motherboard
\begin{itemize}
\item Charge can stay in motherboard, usually in a capacitor somewhere
\item Disconnect power, remove battery
\item Hold power button down for 30s
\item Usually, removes residual voltage from motherboard
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Battery}
\label{sec:orgc283e0f}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{./images/1-1ManyBatteries.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{Some batteries}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item Most laptop batteries are lithium ion (Li-ion)
\item With time and repeated charges, the battery's ability to hold and maintain charge will diminish.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Touchpad}
\label{sec:org7f08a29}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Touchpads}  Most laptops now have touchpads for navigating with a graphical user environment, taking the place of an external mouse
\item Touchpads can be enabled and disabled through system preferences, at times through a keyboard function key, and are prone to their own set of dysfunctions
\begin{itemize}
\item Touchpads can become dirty, unplugged from the central components, or inadvertantly touched and activated by users.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Plastics/frames – Speaker}
\label{sec:org8312a65}
\begin{itemize}
\item Sound from laptops are generated by internal speakers.  
\begin{itemize}
\item A number of things can go wrong with these, including:
\begin{itemize}
\item being physically disconnected from the control units of the computer
\item being inadvertantly turned off by the user.
\item Speakers are also more vulnerable to damage by liquid and dust.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item Laptop frames are generally made out of plastic to reduce weight and decrease cost.
\begin{itemize}
\item Some laptops include both plastic and metal components in their frame to increase durability.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{System board}
\label{sec:org0d7e3ab}
\begin{itemize}
\item ``System board'' is a term that designates the matrix that connects all the most important components of a computer.  
\begin{itemize}
\item Modules such as the CPU, RAM, and power management are usually found on the system board.
\begin{itemize}
\item Unlike desktop computers, in which there are a number of standard system board types and sizes, most system boards are custom designed for each model of laptop to meet contraints of power and weight.
\begin{itemize}
\item As such, they are much more difficult to repair than their desktop cousins.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{CPU}
\label{sec:orgd23ee44}
\begin{itemize}
\item CPUs for laptops are designed with power consumption in mind.
\begin{itemize}
\item CPUs for mobile devices are usually smaller, lighter, use less power, and generate less heat than their desktop counterparts.
\item This also means that different features are integrated into the CPU that might be separated in a desktop computer.  
\begin{itemize}
\item For example, memory and video controllers might be integrated into a CPU designed for a laptop, whereas in a desktop they might be different system cards.
\end{itemize}

\item Mobile CPUs are not generally replaceable or upgradeable.
\begin{itemize}
\item When a component of a system board fails, the quickest and cheapest response is usually to switch out the entire board.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{1.2 – Given a scenario, install components within the display of a laptop.}
\label{sec:org7cfb6d8}

\subsection*{Types}
\label{sec:org32d6d34}
\subsubsection*{Types of displays: \textbf{LCD}}
\label{sec:org73c3bb0}
\begin{itemize}
\item Liquid Crystal Display
\begin{itemize}
\item In these displays, light shines through a sheet of liquid crystal which changes shape with varying electrical current.
\begin{itemize}
\item The liquid crystal itself provides no illumination and must be backlit.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{./images/1-2-LCDpanel.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{inside an LCD}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item In backlit LCDs, the lighting is generally provided by a cold cathode fluorescent lamp (CCFL) which is powered by an inverter whose task is to convert DC power from the laptop back into AC power (\textbf{picture}).  Both the inverter and / or the CCFL can fail and require replacement.
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{./images/1-2-InverterCCFL.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{an inverter and a CCFL}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item An important step to test \textbf{any} potentially failing screen is to see if the computer can be connected to an external monitor.
\begin{itemize}
\item In addition, if only the backlight or inverter has failed on an LCD screen, you should still be able to see images on the screen with the aid of a flashlight.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{OLED}
\label{sec:orgae3975a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Organic Light Emitting Diode
\begin{itemize}
\item No backlight required, organic diodes emit light in response to electrical current.
\begin{itemize}
\item The organic compounds can be ``printed'' on almost any subtrate.
\item These screens are usually thinnner and lighter than LCDs, but use more power.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=1\textwidth]{./images/1-2-LCD-OLED.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{LCD and OLED panels}
\end{center}
\subsection*{WiFi antenna connector/placement}
\label{sec:org7fa087b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Laptops can have a number of different antennae, including WiFi, Bluetooth, and cellular.
\begin{itemize}
\item WiFi cards have some different form and size factors, and most usually their antennae wrap around the display of the device.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{./images/1-1-M2WiFiCard.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{An M.2 WiFi card}
\end{center}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{./images/1-1-PCIeWiFi.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{A PCIe WiFi card}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Webcam}
\label{sec:orgd30f7c8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Webcams are usually located in the frame of the display.
\item Care must be taken to not damage them when the display is being repaired.
\begin{itemize}
\item Cameras are generally controlled by the operating system.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Microphone}
\label{sec:orgeab6afd}
\begin{itemize}
\item Microphones can be located anywhere on the frame of the laptop 
\begin{itemize}
\item Will not always be prominant or obvious
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Digitizer/touchscreen}
\label{sec:org834fe4c}

\begin{itemize}
\item Some laptops or tablets will have \textbf{digitizers} as part of their displays, allowing them to be used as touchscreens.
\item Anything which can damage the display can damage the touchscreen.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Quiz!}
\label{sec:org790f4c0}
\section*{1.3 – Given a scenario, use appropriate laptop features.}
\label{sec:orgb36febf}

\subsection*{Docking station}
\label{sec:org3465816}
\begin{itemize}
\item A docking station allows the user to connect their laptop to an external keyboard, display, mouse, and external video cards
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Port replicator}
\label{sec:org1debb11}
\begin{itemize}
\item A port replicator is similar to a docking station, but does not have external expansion cards.
\begin{itemize}
\item A port replicator will allow the laptop to connect to a number of other peripheral devices.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth :placement[h]]{./images/1-3-PortReplicator.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Look at all those ports!}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Physical laptop lock and cable lock}
\label{sec:org8482405}
\begin{itemize}
\item One of the advantages of a laptop is also one of its weaknesses.
\begin{itemize}
\item They are light and mobile, which means that they are easier to steal
\begin{itemize}
\item Cable locks are a way of making your laptop more secure.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth :placement[h]]{./images/1-3-cableLock2.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{A cable lock}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Rotating/removable screens}
\label{sec:org5f8237f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Some laptops have displays that can be rotated or detatched, making them more like tablets.
\begin{itemize}
\item These devices are more likely to have a digital stylus for input.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth :placement[h]]{./images/1-3-Asus-flip.png}
\captionof{figure}{ASUS C302 Flip}
\end{center}

\section*{1.4 – Compare and contrast characteristics of various types of other mobile devices.}
\label{sec:orgb0327d7}

\subsection*{Tablets}
\label{sec:org24e00e3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Tablets, in many ways, are sort of like giant smartphones
\begin{itemize}
\item accomplish the same ends and share similar technologies
\item Their operating systems can be:
\begin{itemize}
\item Android (an open operating system developed by Google)
\item or iOS (a proprietary operating system developed by Apple).
\item Generally measure between 6 and 11 inches diagonally.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Smartphones}
\label{sec:org95a1179}
\begin{itemize}
\item Devices focussed on mobile communication
\begin{itemize}
\item in addition to voice commuication usually have access to email, productivity software, music or video.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Wearable technology devices}
\label{sec:org330c7d4}
\subsubsection*{Smart watches}
\label{sec:orgea4ba8f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Like smart phones, only smaller and on your wrist!
\begin{itemize}
\item Wireless ability can include WiFi, cellular, or Bluetooth / local connections to your phone.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Fitness monitors}
\label{sec:org22bd4e1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Bands that can fit around your wrist or elsewhere
\begin{itemize}
\item Monitor things such as heartrate and respiration
\item Then send that data wirelessly to your phone or another computer
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{VR/AR headsets}
\label{sec:orgfa82945}
\begin{itemize}
\item Still more promise than reality
\begin{itemize}
\item Designed to replace reality with a computer-generated version
\begin{itemize}
\item Could be used for games or industrial design.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{E-readers}
\label{sec:org0d38b8f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Digital devices allowing the reading of books
\item Share many characteristics with tablets and smartphones.
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{GPS}
\label{sec:orge9f6c18}
\begin{itemize}
\item Now more often incorporated in phones
\begin{itemize}
\item GPS stands for ``Global Positioning System) and uses satellites to fix your location
\item Requires power and a view of the sky.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{1.5 – Given a scenario, connect and configure accessories and ports of other mobile devices.}
\label{sec:orge9e0f43}

\subsection*{Connection Types}
\label{sec:orgd545b04}
\subsubsection*{Wired connections}
\label{sec:orgf445d37}
\paragraph*{Micro-USB / Mini-USB / USB-C}
\label{sec:orgd4a8d9e}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{./images/1-5-MobileDeviceConnectors.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Different mobile ports and connectors}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item The timescale of adoption has gone like this: 
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{even older connectors} --> Mini USB-B --> Micro USB-B --> USB-C
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\paragraph*{USB connectors}
\label{sec:org3318e03}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{USB-B}: Mini USB-B found only in older devices today.
\begin{itemize}
\item The EU standardized Micro USB-B for most mobile devices
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{USB-C}: Newer USB format
\begin{itemize}
\item 24-pin double-sided USB connector
\item Symmetrical
\item Can be used for both hosts and devices
\item Both USB 3.1 and USB 2.0
\item Can carry power, data, analog (audio)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\paragraph*{Lightning}
\label{sec:org583f441}
\begin{itemize}
\item Proprietary Apple format
\begin{itemize}
\item 8-pin digital signals
\item Used on iPad, iPhone, iPod
\item Generally more durable than micro USB-B
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{./images/1-5-LightningConnector.png}
\captionof{figure}{Lightning connector}
\end{center}

\paragraph*{Tethering}
\label{sec:orgc1da3c9}
\begin{itemize}
\item Allows another device (laptop, desktop, other smartphones) to use your mobile device's internet connection
\item Tethering can be wired (using USB / Lightning connectors
\item or wireless, using Bluetooth
\item Sometimes needs to be specifically enabled by a wireless carrier (Verizon!)
\end{itemize}

\paragraph*{Proprietary vendor-specific ports (communication/power)}
\label{sec:orgf5e2241}
\begin{itemize}
\item Older connectors had diverse shapes and capabilities
\begin{itemize}
\item Different connectors for power, data.
\end{itemize}
\item A maddening situation that was partly sorted out by the EU
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Wireless}
\label{sec:org598f3f5}
\paragraph*{NFC}
\label{sec:org2d4c151}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Near Field Communication}
\item Short range wireless communication using 13.56 MHz frequency
\item Transmits 100-400 kb/s - not much! Slower than Bluetooth
\item Used for transmitting data between devices (contact info, MP3s, photos)
\begin{itemize}
\item Can communicate with POS terminals for contactless payment - acts like a smart card
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{./images/1-5-NFCpayment.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Also used with NFC tags
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{./images/1-5-NFCtag.png}
\captionof{figure}{NFC tags and phone}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Bluetooth}
\label{sec:org368adc0}
\subsubsection*{Enable Bluetooth}
\label{sec:orgb7d7a3a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Short-range, usually 10 meters or so.  Part of a PAN (personal area network)
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Enable pairing}
\label{sec:orgc3deb2c}
Discussed above
\subsubsection*{Find a device for pairing}
\label{sec:orgcfe6693}
Discussed above
\subsubsection*{Enter the appropriate PIN code}
\label{sec:org76d1f77}
Also above!
\subsubsection*{Test connectivity}
\label{sec:org1f70c21}
\begin{itemize}
\item Worth testing after pairing is enabled
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Corporate and ISP email configuration}
\label{sec:orgd7b9a09}
\subsubsection*{Mail protocols}
\label{sec:orgbb109fe}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lrll}
E-Mail Protocl & Original port number & Secure port number & Stands for\\
\hline
 &  &  & \\
SMTP & 25 & 465 or 587 & Secure Mail Transfer Protocol\\
 &  &  & [``Send Mail To Person'')\\
POP3 & 110 & 995 & Post Office Protocol\\
IMAP & 143 & 993 & Internet Mail Access Protocol\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Sending mail - SMTP
\item Retrieving mail - POP3, IMAP
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Post Office Protocol 3 (POP3)}
\label{sec:org82c6a8c}
\begin{itemize}
\item downloads email to local client
\begin{itemize}
\item optionally deletes from server
\end{itemize}
\item configuration: 
\begin{itemize}
\item name of POP3 server
\item Username and password
\end{itemize}
\item network ports: 
\begin{itemize}
\item POP3: tcp/110
\item SSL (Secure Socket Layer): POP3S: tcp/995
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Internet Message Access Protocol (IMAP4)}
\label{sec:orgc0fe293}
\begin{itemize}
\item Accesses mail on a central server
\begin{itemize}
\item mail stays on server, can be accessed by different email clients simultaneously
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item IMAP4 can have folders
\begin{itemize}
\item configuration: 
\begin{itemize}
\item name of IMAP server
\item username and password
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item network ports:
\begin{itemize}
\item IMAP: tcp/143
\item SSL: IMAPS: tcp/993
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.2\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/1-6-imap4.png}
\captionof{figure}{a meaningless image\ldots{} or is it?}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Sending email - SMTP}
\label{sec:org78a94e8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Sending mail from device to mail server
\item some kind of authentication required
\item network ports:
\begin{itemize}
\item SMTP without autherntication (now rarely used): tcp/25
\item with authentication: tcp/587
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Integrated commercial provider email configuration}
\label{sec:org6076db9}
\subsubsection*{iCloud}
\label{sec:org724867e}
Apple email, IMAP4 only
\subsubsection*{Google/Inbox}
\label{sec:org9b6cef3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Google email, can use IMAP4 or POP3
\item Can split emails into folders or tabs
\item Inbox was cool but has been retired
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Exchange Online}
\label{sec:org4524110}
\begin{itemize}
\item Commercially available service version of corporate Exchange
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Yahoo}
\label{sec:org5b535ac}
\begin{itemize}
\item IMAP4 and POP3 support
\item This still exists, as does AOL, oddly
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{PRL updates / PRI updates / baseband updates}
\label{sec:org0d066d8}
\begin{itemize}
\item A smartphone is a radio.  Cellular networks are very different from WiFi or Bluetooth
\item Communications happen through a \textbf{baseband radio processor}
\item \textbf{PRL} - Preferred Roaming List
\begin{itemize}
\item in CDMA (Code Division Multiple Access).  Allows phone to connect to the right tower.
\item Updated OTA (Over The Air)
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{PRI} - Product Release Instructions
\begin{itemize}
\item Radio settings such as ID numbers, network codes, country codes
\item Updated OTA
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Radio firmware}
\label{sec:org2570114}
\begin{itemize}
\item the radio processor has proprietary firmware, which must be updated occasionally
\begin{itemize}
\item Most updates done OTA (Over The Air) mostly invisible to user
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{IMEI vs. IMSI}
\label{sec:orgd5f5d84}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{IMEI} - International Mobile Station Equipment Identity
\begin{itemize}
\item Identifies an individual mobile device
\item Every phone has a different IMEI
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{IMSI} - International Mobile Subscriber Identity
\begin{itemize}
\item Identifies the subscriber (you!)
\item Provisioned by the SIM card
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{VPN}
\label{sec:org9fdbed6}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{VPN} Virtual Private Network
\begin{itemize}
\item We will discuss this concept further, later
\item But for now, this can turn your device into a VPN endpoint
\item VPNs allow for secure, encrypted communication between your device and a VPN server
\item When using VPN, your device appears to be on the network of the VPN server
\item This is often used when out of the office or home to access things that only authorized users of that network can access.
\item Can be part of the phone / device OS
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{1.7 – Given a scenario, use methods to perform mobile device synchronization.}
\label{sec:org19a2313}

\subsection*{Synchronization methods}
\label{sec:orge4a84d7}
\begin{itemize}
\item What is synchronization and why do it?
\begin{itemize}
\item Being able to keep information current over all devices you use
\item Now is often performed wirelessly (over mobile network or 802.11 wireless)
\item There are dangers too!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Synchronize to the cloud}
\label{sec:org915e409}
\begin{itemize}
\item Many things in your data world are probably already synchronized without you noticing
\item That is how prevalent this system and concept is
\item With Android - many services synchronized through Google
\item Apple iOS - through iCloud
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Synchronize to the desktop}
\label{sec:orgb0d0bf8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Depends on OS and sufficient disk space
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Synchronize to the automobile}
\label{sec:orgd9ef81a}
\begin{itemize}
\item via Bluetooth to media player / car computer
\item Android Auto, iOS CarPlay
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Types of data to synchronize}
\label{sec:org52ea595}

\begin{itemize}
\item Contacts
\item Applications
\item Email
\item Pictures
\item Music
\item Videos
\item Calendar
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Bookmarks
\item Documents
\item Location data
\item Social media data
\item E-books
\item Passwords
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Mutual authentication for multiple services (SSO)}
\label{sec:orge97e51f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Single Sign-On (SSO):
\begin{itemize}
\item an important (and cool) concept that will discuss again
\end{itemize}
\item Simply, using a single identification to access multiple different services
\item Without having to sign in each time
\item Google and Apple use these widely for their services
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Connection types to enable synchronization}
\label{sec:orga6484f2}
\begin{itemize}
\item Although synchronization is now usually handled wirelessly, there was a time when it wasn't, and for some things you still need wires.  Here are some.
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/1-7-synchronizationPlugs.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Connection types for wired synchronization}
\end{center}
\section*{2.1 – Compare and contrast TCP and UDP ports, protocols, and their purposes.}
\label{sec:orgd33d2bb}

\subsection*{Brief Introduction to IP}
\label{sec:org3bca25f}
\begin{itemize}
\item How do 1s and 0s move from one place to another over a network?
\item Brief reflection on the absurdity of sending all those poor 1s and 0s by themselves
\item We decided to put them in little boxes or \textbf{packets} that help them along their way
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Sketch of some packets}
\label{sec:orge74fd6f}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-1-IPpacketSketch.png}
\captionof{figure}{Here are some packets}
\end{center}

\subsection*{TCP vs. UDP}
\label{sec:org20c3cc8}
\subsubsection*{\textbf{TCP} - Transmission Control Protocol}
\label{sec:orgec9107c}
\begin{itemize}
\item ``Connection-oriented'' - every packet is checked for delivery
\item \emph{3-way handshake}:
\begin{enumerate}
\item SYN: client computer initiates connection with a synchronization request (SYN packet)
\item SYN + ACK: Server responds with a synchronization / acknowledgment packet
\item ACK: Client sends acknowledgment packet
\end{enumerate}
\item Then the connection is established - a \emph{TCP socket connection}
\item Every single packet is accounted for in TCP - flow control, etc
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{\textbf{UDP} - User Datagram Protocol}
\label{sec:org9822a4f}
\begin{itemize}
\item ``Connectionless sessions'' - if a packet is missed or dropped, no big deal
\item This can be faster - none of that back and forth
\item But no error-connection
\item Good for things that are streaming, like voice or media where a few dropped packets won't change much
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{A diagram of TCP \& UDP}
\label{sec:org982a1b4}
\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-1-udp-tcpDiagram.jpg}
\caption{A diagram of IP protocols}
\end{figure}


\newpage
\begin{landscape}
\subsection*{Ports and Protocols}
\label{sec:org2649fe0}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Protocols and Ports you are expected to know for the A+}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|l|l|l|l|}
Protocol & Port & Name & Description\\
\hline
FTP & tcp/20, tcp21 & File Transfer Protocol & Sends and receives files between systems\\
SSH & tcp/22 & Secure Shell & Encrypted console access\\
Telnet & tcp/23 & Telecommunication Network & Insecure console access\\
SMTP & tcp/25 & Simple Mail Transfer Protocol & Transfer email between mail servers\\
DNS & udp/53, tcp/53 & Domain Name System & Convert domain names to IP addresses\\
HTTP & tcp/80 & Hypertext Transfer Protocol & Web server communication\\
HTTPS & tcp/443 & Hypertext Transfer Protocol Secure & Web server communication with encryption\\
POP3 & tcp/110 & Post Office Protocol version 3 & Receive email into a email client\\
IMAP4 & tcp/143 & Internet Message Access Protocol v4 & A newer email client protocol\\
RDP & tcp/3389 & Remote Desktop Protocol & Graphical display of remote devices\\
NetBIOS & udp/137 & NetBIOS name service & Register, remove, and find Windows services by name\\
NetBIOS & udp/138 & NetBIOS datagram service & Windows connecConless data transfer\\
NetBIOS & tcp/139 & NetBIOS session service & Windows connecCon-oriented data transfer\\
SMB & tcp/445 & Server Message Block & Windows file transfers and printer sharing\\
AFP & tcp/548 & Apple Filing Protocol & Mac OS file transfers\\
SLP & tcp/427, udp/427 & Service Location Protocol & Find Mac OS services by name\\
DHCP & udp/67, udp/68 & Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol & Automate the IP address configuration process\\
LDAP & tcp/389 & Lightweight Directory Access Protocol & Directory services\\
SNMP & udp/161 & Simple Network Management Protocol & Gather metrics and manage network devices\\
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\end{landscape}

\section*{2.2 – Compare and contrast common networking hardware devices.}
\label{sec:org17e0d90}
\subsection*{Network Interface Card}
\label{sec:orgb8b6238}
\begin{itemize}
\item Found in \emph{every} device that attaches to the network
\item Every NIC has a MAC address (Media Access Control)
\item Specific to which type of connection - ethernet, wireless, etc
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Repeater}
\label{sec:org790fda4}
\begin{itemize}
\item Receives a signal and re-sends it
\item No decisions or rules to follow
\item Used to:
\begin{itemize}
\item Boost connections
\item Convert from one network media to another (i.e. fiber --> copper)
\item Extend wireless LAN
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-2-Repeater.png}
\captionof{figure}{Repeater}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Hub}
\label{sec:org92521be}
\begin{itemize}
\item ``Multi-port repeater''
\begin{itemize}
\item Sends message to all devices
\item Before routers, this is how data was distributed in network
\item Everything half-duplex
\item Less efficient as network speeds increase
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-2-NetworkHubDiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{Network Hub}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Bridge}
\label{sec:orgcfe87f3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Makes packet forwarding decisions in software
\begin{itemize}
\item Connects different physical networks
\item Distributes traffic based on MAC address
\item Wireless Access Points act as bridges
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Switches}
\label{sec:orgbf70bce}
\begin{itemize}
\item Bridging done in hardware - faster
\begin{itemize}
\item Forwards traffic based on data link address
\item Lots of ports, features, especially when managed
\item Vital for large internal networks
\item This is where VLANs are configured
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Managed Switches}
\label{sec:org50a52c0}
\begin{itemize}
\item VLAN support
\item Can organize traffic priorities (i.e. voice over data)
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Unmanaged Switches}
\label{sec:org45dacea}
\begin{itemize}
\item No configuration, no VPNs
\item Cheap!
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Routers}
\label{sec:orga772bd7}
\begin{itemize}
\item Routes traffic between subnets
\item Makes forwarding decision based on IP address
\item Can connect diverse network types
\begin{itemize}
\item Can incorporate LAN, WAN, copper, fiber
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-2-Router.png}
\captionof{figure}{IP address assignments through and to a router}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Access points}
\label{sec:org1dc916e}
\begin{itemize}
\item A Wireless Access Point (WAP) functions as a network bridge
\item Makes forwarding decisions based on MAC address
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-2-WirelessAccessPoint.png}
\captionof{figure}{Network with WAP}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Firewall}
\label{sec:orgad761a8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Filters traffic by port number
\begin{itemize}
\item OSI Layer 4 (TCP / UDP)
\end{itemize}
\item Vitally important for any network
\item Provides protection against intrusion, by bots or individuals
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-2-HomeNetworkFirewall.png}
\captionof{figure}{Home network with firewall}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Cable modem}
\label{sec:org6bf5526}
\begin{itemize}
\item Broadband modem
\item Different types of traffic can be accommodated by modem
\begin{itemize}
\item i.e. data, voice
\end{itemize}
\item Data on a cable network:
\begin{itemize}
\item DOCSIS (Data Over Cable Service Interface Specification
\end{itemize}
\item High speed - 4 Mbits/sec to 250 Mbits/sec
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{DSL modem}
\label{sec:org180d0ba}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{DSL}- Digital Subscriber Line
\begin{itemize}
\item ADSL - asymmetric, meaning that download is faster than upload
\end{itemize}
\item Data over regular copper telephone line
\item Needs to be \textasciitilde{}10,000 feet from CO
\item Speeds, errors decrease with distance from CO
\item Highest speeds around 52 Mbits/sec, usually much much lower
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DSL diagram}
\label{sec:orgb25d0e0}
.\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/2-2-DSLdiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{Home network with firewall}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Patch panel}
\label{sec:org65d1a12}
\begin{itemize}
\item Network of internal connections made from WAN
\begin{itemize}
\item RJ45 connections, individual runs made to wall or floor sockets
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-2-PatchPanel.png}
\captionof{figure}{Network patch panel diagram}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Power over Ethernet (PoE)}
\label{sec:org0d76cfb}
\begin{itemize}
\item Power can be routed along Ethernet cables, very useful especially for distant or hard-to-reach areas
\begin{itemize}
\item Power ``injected'' into Ethernet cables
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Injectors}
\label{sec:orgede0c34}
\begin{itemize}
\item Injectors placed alongside cable initiation
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-2-POEinjector.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{POE injector}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{POE Switch}
\label{sec:orgdc46ace}
\begin{itemize}
\item POE can be injected into network cables by special switches
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Ethernet over Power}
\label{sec:org76668dd}
\begin{itemize}
\item Power-line communication (PLC)
\item Data flows along household electrical wires
\item All kinds of problems with electrical junctions, often slow and subject to interference
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Addendum: OSI Model}
\label{sec:org9374a79}
\begin{itemize}
\item The OSI model is not specifically part of the A+ 1001 objectives, but!
\begin{itemize}
\item It is a model that you will see throughout your time in IT.
\item My experience is that having even a vague understanding of this model will help you sort out the nature and purpose of some of the network devices we have just talked about.
\end{itemize}

\item So mostly this is just here for you to look at so that you will recognize the terms later.
\end{itemize}

[[./images/2-2-OSIlayers.jpeg]\}
\begin{itemize}
\item Two favorite mnemonic devices for the OSI model:
\begin{itemize}
\item (bottom-up) Please Do Not Throw Sausage Pizza Away
\item (top-down) All People Seem To Need Data Processing
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{2.3 – Given a scenario, install and configure a basic wired/wireless SOHO network.}
\label{sec:orgdb21867}
\begin{itemize}
\item SOHO - Small Office / Home Office
\item A cool online resource: practice on a virtual Linksys router:
\begin{itemize}
\item \url{http://ui.linksys.com/WRT54G/v8/8.00.0/StaRouter.htm}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Router/switch functionality}
\label{sec:org4f308a4}
\begin{itemize}
\item Standard SOHO router is an all-in-one device:
\begin{itemize}
\item Modem, router, switch, Wireless Access Point, firewall, etc
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/2-3-LinksysRouter.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A Linksys WRT 1900 AC - router, wireless and wired connections}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Connecting the WAN
\item Wired connection to local devices
\item Unless you want specialized stuff (VLANs, etc) switching and routing happens under the hood
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Wireless Access Point (WAP) settings}
\label{sec:org8b67504}
\begin{itemize}
\item Enable and set different frequencies - 2.4GHz / 5 GHz
\item These days most routers will have both
\item Configure SSID - this is the \emph{name} of the WAP that is broadcast
\begin{itemize}
\item Eternal question of different SSIDs for frequencies
\item Most routers and devices can auto-switch frequencies to some degree
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Security mode
\begin{itemize}
\item WPA2 preferable - WEP vulnerable, WPA (WiFi Protected Access) vlunerable as well
\end{itemize}
\item In order of decreasing security:
\begin{enumerate}
\item WPA2 + AES (Advanced Encryption Security)
\item WPA + AES
\item WPA + TKIP/AES
\item WPA + TKIP
\item WEP
\item Open network (no security)
\end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Channel selection on a WAP}
\label{sec:org8d7241b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Selecting channels: other nearby WAPs can crowd channels
\item Some WAPs / routers can scan local wireless channels; apps for phones and computers can do this as well
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{IP addressing}
\label{sec:orgab7aa04}
\begin{itemize}
\item On WAN side: IP address usually assigned by ISP via DHCP
\item LAN side:
\begin{itemize}
\item Internal IP address, subnet mask of router
\item DHCP address range for other devices on network
\item DNS server address can be set manually, but are often the ISP's by default
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Network Interface Card (NIC) configuration}
\label{sec:orge98bbad}
\subsubsection*{Wired}
\label{sec:orgedc2fc5}
\begin{itemize}
\item Wired ports on router usually pre-configured
\item auto speed and duplex by default
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Wireless}
\label{sec:org5b33a40}
\begin{itemize}
\item Mostly just enable / disable
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{End-user device configuration}
\label{sec:orgfc87ddf}
\begin{itemize}
\item Usually done automatically, will set up speed, duplex, and DHCP without intervention from user
\item But there are many things you can change:
\begin{itemize}
\item subnet mask
\item Default gateway
\item DNS servers
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{IoT device configuration}
\label{sec:orgb6f9041}
\begin{itemize}
\item Oh, the Internet of Things
\begin{itemize}
\item Very hip and buzzy term, but encompasses a wide range of interesting devices
\item Usually involving home automation and the communication between various appliances / devices and things on the LAN or WAN
\item Many security issues, but can be fun and handy
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{IOT: Thermostat}
\label{sec:org07bb2c8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Thermostat can be set remotely, can be set to change depending on temperature, can be set to start heating / air conditioning when you leave work
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{IOT: Light switches}
\label{sec:orge47b9e1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Same - remote turning on / off, can be set to change colors / brighness on time of day and your activities
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{IOT: Security cameras}
\label{sec:org8b3f73d}
\begin{itemize}
\item i.e. Nest, Ring (controversial issue with police seeking data)
\begin{itemize}
\item other security cameras can be set up and monitored remotely
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{IOT: Door locks}
\label{sec:orgcd06978}
\begin{itemize}
\item Can be set to open to particular people, only at particular times, etc.
\begin{itemize}
\item Can also be managed remotely, in conjunction with a security camera perhaps
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Cable/DSL modem configuration}
\label{sec:org3b6ff61}
\begin{itemize}
\item ``Modem'' - /Mo/dulator /dem/odulator
\begin{itemize}
\item Converts analog signals to digital signals
\item Both will have particular settings, usually managed by your ISP
\item Fiber does not use a ``modem'' but uses a similar device called an ONT (Optical Network Terminal) which divides up and apportions the signal (voice, data, telephone, televison)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Firewall settings}
\label{sec:org691f7c4}
\subsubsection*{DMZ - Demilitarized Zone}
\label{sec:orgef88fa6}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{./images/2-3-DMZ.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{DMZ, WAN, and LAN}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item If you are running a service that requires access to and from the WAN (mail server, media server, Minecraft server, etc) place in the DMZ to protect your LAN
\item But generally don't do this from home, and often more secure to use port forwarding
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{NAT}
\label{sec:org24873f5}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{NAT} - Network Address translation
\item Router translates all internal LAN IP addresses (i.e. 192.168.x.x or 10.x.x.x) to the external IP address of the router
\item This is required due to limitations of IPv4
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/2-3-IPv4vsIPv6.png}
\captionof{figure}{IPv4 vs IPv6}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Port forwarding}
\label{sec:orgd1482aa}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{./images/2-3-PortForwardingDiagram.jpeg}
\captionof{figure}{Port forwarding}
\end{center}
\textbf{PORT FORWARDING}

\begin{itemize}
\item Access to a machine in the LAN from \emph{outside} the LAN
\begin{itemize}
\item External IP and port number mapped by router to an internal machine
\item Can be called Static NAT or Destination NAT
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{UPnP}
\label{sec:org6fc8023}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{UPnP} Universal Plug and Play
\begin{itemize}
\item Allowed network devices to automatically find and join LAN
\item As you can imagine, this seemed like a good idea but turned out to be a huge security risk
\item You should almost always disable UPnP
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Whitelist/blacklist}
\label{sec:org8cb61c0}
\begin{itemize}
\item You can set up your firewall to only allow in approved connections (whitelisting). This is hard to maintain, especially if others are using your internet
\begin{itemize}
\item Or deny access from things you don't like (blacklisting)
\begin{itemize}
\item Can block specific domains, IP addresses, sites, even geographic regions
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{MAC filtering}
\label{sec:orgd365b28}
\begin{itemize}
\item Remember how the MAC (Media Access Control) address is like the individual name of the device (Layer 2 of OSI model)?
\begin{itemize}
\item So you can restrict access to your internet to only specific MAC addresses, allowing only known, pre-approved devices to have access to your network
\item This seems like it would be a good security idea, right?
\item Except it isn't.  MAC addresses can be spoofed and rewritten on the device's NIC, and all an intruder would need to do would be to discover one of the approved MAC addresses and spoof it.
\item ``Security through obscurity'' - not the last time you will hear this
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{QoS}
\label{sec:orgca283ec}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{QOS} - Quality of Service.
\begin{itemize}
\item Can rank priority of different services or protocols on your network regarding access to bandwidth.
\item VOIP usually high
\item Can even set this by time of day - only give priority to large downloads late at night for example
\item Can even rank particular ports, applications, or machines by MAC address as higher priority
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Configuring a SOHO router: Wireless settings}
\label{sec:org27ee9fd}
\subsubsection*{Encryption}
\label{sec:orgb58becb}
\begin{itemize}
\item Should configure for the best encryption available
\begin{itemize}
\item i.e. WPA3-AES
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Channels}
\label{sec:orgf615164}
\begin{itemize}
\item Can check to see if channels are available
\begin{itemize}
\item Using a WiFi scanner
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{QoS}
\label{sec:org7eafbb1}
\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{Quality of Service}
\begin{itemize}
\item Configures the priorities of different signals through the network
\begin{itemize}
\item For example, you would usually rank voice over IP (VOIP) higher than file server traffic
\item But not always!
\begin{itemize}
\item Will depend on the nature of your network and your priorities
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{2.4 – Compare and contrast wireless networking protocols.}
\label{sec:org426bfcd}
\subsection*{802.11 Wireless Standards}
\label{sec:orgf04a022}

\begin{itemize}
\item Institute of Electrical and Electronic Engineers maintains these standards
\end{itemize}
\newpage
\begin{landscape}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{llllll}
IEEE & Frequency & Max speed & Max speed & MIMO & Transmission Range\\
Standard &  & per stream & total & streams & \\
\hline
802.11 & 2.4GHz RF & 1 to 2 Mbps & 1 to 2 Mbps & None & 20 feet indoors.\\
802.11a & 5GHz & 54 Mbps & 54 Mbps & None & 25 to 75 feet indoors\\
802.11b & 2.4GHz & 11 Mbps & 11 Mbps & None & Up to 150 feet indoors\\
802.11g & 2.4GHz & 54 Mbps & 54 Mbps & None & Up to 150 feet indoors\\
802.11n & 2.4GHz/5GHz & 150 Mbps & 600 Mbps & 4 MIMO & 175+ feet indoors\\
802.11ac & 5GHz & 866.7 Mbps & 6.8 Gbps & 8 MU-MIMO & 175+ feet indoors\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\end{landscape}

\begin{itemize}
\item MIMO - Multiple Input and Multiple Output.  Increases speed by using multiple antennas exploiting multipath propagation

\item Transmission Range - strongly affected by indoor building materials
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{802.11a}
\label{sec:orgb38a00d}
\begin{itemize}
\item a and b were the first wireless standards, in 1999
\item a operates in 5 Ghz range
\item 5 GHz is a higher frequency - more likely to be affected by objects and materials
\item But generally a less crowded frequency
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{802.11b}
\label{sec:org1f2e276}
\begin{itemize}
\item in 2.4 GHz
\item 2.4 GHz has better range, but more prone to interference
\item many electronic devices broadcast on 2.4 GHz range - microwave ovens, cordless phones, baby monitors
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{802.11g}
\label{sec:org9b74d70}
\begin{itemize}
\item Also 2.4 GHz, in 2003
\item backwards compatible with 802.11b
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{802.11n}
\label{sec:org0a9f7c9}
\begin{itemize}
\item Update in 2009, transmits at 2.4 GHz or 5 GHz
\item First protocol to use MIMO, enable faster theoretical speeds, as long as the receiving device supports MIMO
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{802.11ac}
\label{sec:org49cbe13}
\begin{itemize}
\item Update to protocol in 2014
\item 5 GHz only
\item if devices can support MIMO, theoretically very fast
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Frequencies}
\label{sec:org896d0d7}
\subsubsection*{2.4 GHz}
\label{sec:org967abaa}
\begin{itemize}
\item as above, less prone to interference from intervening materials, but more crowded spectrum
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{5 GHz}
\label{sec:orgd6ff106}
\begin{itemize}
\item Theoretically faster, less prone to interference on spectrum
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Channels}
\label{sec:org1e14f6f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Channels have different bandwidths
\item 802.11a, b, and g had 20 MHz channel widths
\item 802.11n was able to first bond channels together, using 40 MHZ channels
\begin{itemize}
\item However, 40 MHz channel in 2.4 GHz soaks up a lot of the bandwidth - if you have neighbors, this is not very kind
\end{itemize}
\item 802.11ac uses 80 MHz and up to 160 MHz channels
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Wireless spectra and channels}
\label{sec:org0db527a}
\begin{figure}[htbp]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=1.2\textwidth]{./images/2-4-WirelessSpectrumsNA.png}
\caption{2.4 GHz and 5 GHz spectra and available channels in North America}
\end{figure}

Non-available frequencies are usually those preserved for the use of aviation and military

\subsection*{RFID}
\label{sec:orga10495e}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{RFID} - Radio Frequency Identification
\begin{itemize}
\item Access badges, inventory management, even a way of tracking my cat!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Zigbee}
\label{sec:org5696033}
\begin{itemize}
\item An IOT communication protocol
\item travels further than Bluetooth, uses less energy than WiFi
\item used or ``smart'' lightbulbs, doors, robo-vacuums
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Z-Wave}
\label{sec:org0513445}
\begin{itemize}
\item Another IOT communication protocol
\item doors, locks, lights, others
\item 900 MHz frequency, little competition in this wavelength
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{2G}
\label{sec:org6b33f6b}
\begin{itemize}
\item back into cellular networking
\item 2G one of the first cellular network protocols
\item Where GSM (Global System for Mobile Communications) and CDMA (Code Division Multiple Access) split
\item OK for voice, terrible for data
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{3G}
\label{sec:orgf96ee41}
\begin{itemize}
\item 1998
\item Slightly better for data, allowed use of GPS, first attempts at mobile video
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{4G}
\label{sec:orgc9a9cce}
\begin{itemize}
\item 2009, first deployed in Sweden
\item Also known as LTE, EDGE (some confusing and conflicting terminology)
\item GSM and CDMA converge
\item Download rates of 150 Mbps
\item LTE-A (LTE Advanced)
\begin{itemize}
\item Download rates up to 300 Mbps
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{5G}
\label{sec:org226004c}
\begin{itemize}
\item Being implemented as we speak
\item Performance improvements but only at higher frequencies - in dense urban environments
\end{itemize}

\section*{2.5 – Summarize the properties and purposes of services provided by networked hosts.}
\label{sec:org9d06aa7}

\subsection*{Server roles}
\label{sec:org80dd823}
\begin{itemize}
\item People make a big deal about the names and roles of different kinds of servers, but when you come right down to it, a server is a computer
\begin{itemize}
\item In corporate or research environments, individual computers might perform a single function.  But in most environments, individual computers can serve multiple server roles
\item This is especially true with the use of virtual machines - many different machines can live in one machine
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Web server}
\label{sec:org6cb45ed}
\begin{itemize}
\item Serves web pages and other resources accessed using HTTP and HTTPS protocols
\begin{itemize}
\item Web pages can have their own dynamic processes, being rebuilt on each visit or being static
\item People have particular feelings about each type of page
\item Some web pages can essentially run their own tiny operating systems and programs
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{File server}
\label{sec:org22d088e}
\begin{itemize}
\item Storage of documents, photos, media
\begin{itemize}
\item These are where Server Message Block (SMB) and Apple Filing Protocol (AFP) live
\item These are the machines most likely to have enormous storage drives, RAID systems (which we will discuss in a bit)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Print server}
\label{sec:orged05ab3}
\begin{itemize}
\item manages printers and printing tasks
\begin{itemize}
\item usually only found in larger network environments
\item Printer protocols:
\begin{itemize}
\item LPD (Line Printer Daemon)
\item IPP (Internet Printing Protocol)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DHCP server}
\label{sec:orgcff9a8a}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{DHCP} - Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol
\begin{itemize}
\item Assigns IP addresses to individual devices on the network
\item In home environment, included in the router
\item In large, enterprise environments this is a crucial service
\begin{itemize}
\item if DHCP goes down, the network starts losing its ability to talk to itself
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DNS server}
\label{sec:org83a39a9}
\begin{itemize}
\item Domain Name System
\begin{itemize}
\item Translates text names to IP addresses
\item Extremely important in enterprise scenarios
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Proxy server}
\label{sec:orga8a3b4b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Server which stands between user and the WAN
\item Serves to protect user, also can restrict where the user can go and what they can do
\item Common in academic environments
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Mail server}
\label{sec:orgb80bb17}
\begin{itemize}
\item Manages email services
\item Crucial in any environment, and extremely complicated to set up and maintain
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Authentication server}
\label{sec:org5a01754}
\begin{itemize}
\item Using applications such as LDAP and Active Directory, manages sign-on and authentication services
\item Extremely important for security
\item Not the kind of thing you use at home
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{SIEM}
\label{sec:org3c5ac3a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Security Information and Event Management
\begin{itemize}
\item logs security issues, intrusion detection
\end{itemize}
\item maintains logs of user access to different parts of network
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{syslog}
\label{sec:orgf1e535a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Another crucial system for maintaining a network
\item A syslog server will maintain log files from other machines on the network
\item massive amounts of space needed, often redundant servers to protect information
\item logs are very important for reconstructing bad events and fixing them, making sure they don't happen again
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Internet appliance}
\label{sec:org1cfab18}

\subsubsection*{IDS}
\label{sec:org9557cf3}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{IDS} - Intrusion Detection System.  Sounds alert if sneaky and bad things are happening - bot attacks, scripting, buffer and kernal overflows
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{IPS}
\label{sec:orgd63bac0}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{IPS} - Intrusion Prevention System
\item Not just reporting like IDS, but actively thwarting attacks
\item FailToBan being a minor example of the kinds of things IPS does
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{UTM}
\label{sec:org61864b7}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{UTM} - Unified Threat Management
\item Very sophisticated firewall with IDS and IPS built in
\item Designed to handle everything - malware, worms, viruses, bad actors, monitors bandwidth use
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{End-point management server}
\label{sec:org752df46}
\begin{itemize}
\item The server to manage servers
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Legacy/embedded systems}
\label{sec:org78bdeea}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Legacy} - IT term for devices / software that are old but still useful.  Many examples of this.
\begin{itemize}
\item Often simply too expensive or time-consuming to replace
\item This is why old COBOL engineers get called up out of retirement
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Embedded Systems} - An electronic device that is simple and only does one thing.  Can manage alarms, door access, sensors, etc.  Will be linked to network, wired or wireless.
\end{itemize}
\newpage
\section*{2.6 – Explain common network configuration concepts.}
\label{sec:orgc845664}
\subsection*{DHCP}
\label{sec:orgd4210df}
\begin{itemize}
\item Before DHCP, all IP addresses on the network were set manually
\item This was a huge pain and could lead to all kinds of problems with different IP address conflicts
\item DHCP automates the process and makes it much smoother
\item DHCP Process:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Discover
\item Offer
\item Request
\item Acknowledge
\end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{DHCP Mechanism}
\label{sec:org8ec0506}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-6-DHCPprocess.png}
\captionof{figure}{DHCP configuration process}
\end{center}

\textbf{DHCP}

\begin{itemize}
\item IP addresses can still be configured manually on each device, but if you are administering a network this should be discouraged
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Reservations}
\label{sec:org8027196}
\begin{itemize}
\item Instead, better to set a static address on the router by setting an IP \textbf{reservation} and associating an IP address with the device's MAC address
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{IP addressing}
\label{sec:org07aef22}
\subsubsection*{Static}
\label{sec:org6512c9b}
\begin{itemize}
\item IP addresses stay the same; the external address of your home internet will stay the same for long periods of time, or forever
\item Particular devices on a network may benefit from having static IP addresses rather than being frequently changed by DHCP
\begin{itemize}
\item These would include printers, file, DNS, or authentication servers
\item Static IP addresses can bet up on each individual device, with different procedures in each operating system
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Dynamic}
\label{sec:orgdcd337a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Changing, usually assigned by DHCP
\item DHCP usually keeps addresses for a week
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{APIPA}
\label{sec:org127d618}
\begin{itemize}
\item Automatic Private IP Addressing
\item When a device cannot contact the DHCP server, it makes up its own IP address in the range 169.254.1.0 - 169.254.255.254
\item Then it keeps trying to find the DHCP server
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{DNS}
\label{sec:org8e3d700}
\begin{itemize}
\item As discussed previously, the \textbf{Domain Name System} (or \textbf{Domain Name Server}) 
\begin{itemize}
\item In setting up a network, the DNS server can be set up in the router, and can also be set up on each machine individually to override the server setting
\item Many different top-level DNS services
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{IPv4 vs. IPv6}
\label{sec:org3dacd7a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Internet Protocol version 4: OSI level 3 address
\begin{itemize}
\item IPv4 is the IP address format you recognize, and will probably continue to use for some time.
\item But many drawbacks, the main one being that we are out of addresses! This is why we need to use NAT.
\item IPv6 will not need to use NAT.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-6-IPv4.png}
\captionof{figure}{IPv4 address format}
\end{center}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{./images/2-6-IPv6.png}
\captionof{figure}{IPv6 address format}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item IPv6 is a 128-bit address - there are 340,282,366,920,938,463,463,374,607,431,768,211,456 addresses (340 undecillion)
\end{itemize}


\subsection*{Subnet mask}
\label{sec:org561ef25}
\begin{itemize}
\item In IPv4, the subnet mask helps the local device to determine its subnet
\begin{itemize}
\item in a standard LAN subnet mask can look like this: 255.255.255.0
\item You will not need to know exactly how this works, (yet!)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Gateway}
\label{sec:orgba3caa0}
\begin{itemize}
\item IP address of the router that governs your access to the WAN
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-6-NetworkGateway.png}
\captionof{figure}{Network Gateway}
\end{center}
\subsection*{\texttt{VPN}  Virtual Private Network}
\label{sec:orgd360876}
\begin{itemize}
\item Uses Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) to create encrypted connection from outside the LAN
\begin{itemize}
\item User can then operate as if they are on the local protected network
\item In other words, a secure connection through insecure network territory
\item Has been particularly important recently, as this allows people to work securely from home
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{VLAN}
\label{sec:org50dfe75}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Virtual Local Area Network} - group of devices in the same broadcast domain
\item A logical division rather than a physical one
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{NAT}
\label{sec:org6bb0e18}
\begin{itemize}
\item Network Address Translation
\begin{itemize}
\item As mentioned, only necessary because of the exhaustion of IPv4 addresses
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/2-6-NATdiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{NAT}
\end{center}

\section*{2.7 – Compare and contrast Internet connection types, network types, and their features.}
\label{sec:orgfa446ca}

\subsection*{Internet connection types}
\label{sec:orgc4f4aa3}

\subsubsection*{Cable \& DSL}
\label{sec:org6a61671}
\begin{itemize}
\item Discussed above
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Dial-up}
\label{sec:org3e21f5e}
\begin{itemize}
\item Old school - establishing network connection over phone lines
\item top speeds 320 kbps
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Fiber}
\label{sec:org50fee72}
\begin{itemize}
\item Highest speed connection currently available to homes
\item High bandwidth, can bundle phone, TV, data
\item Speeds up to 1 Gbit/sec
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Satellite}
\label{sec:org32474ab}
\begin{itemize}
\item Sometimes the only available option in extremely rural areas
\item expensive, high latency
\item line of sight, vulnerable to weather
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{ISDN}
\label{sec:org656a9c8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Ancient but still on the A+ exam, still in use as legacy systems for business (more likely to be a backup connection now).  Two subtypes:
\item BRI - Basic Rate Interface
\begin{itemize}
\item Two 64 kbit/s bearer channels
\item One 16 kbit/s signalling channel
\end{itemize}
\item PRI - Primary Rate Interface
\begin{itemize}
\item over T1 or E1 line
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Line-of-sight wireless Internet service}
\label{sec:orgc0c4f9d}
\begin{itemize}
\item Seen in rural areas and some urban areas
\item WAN sent out by broadcast through network of interlinked antennae, often microwave
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Network types}
\label{sec:org996bdc6}

\begin{itemize}
\item WAN, LAN, PAN, MAN
\item New one we haven't discussed:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{WMN} - Wireless Mesh Network
= All devices connect together in a cloud network
= IOT devices can use this
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{2.8 – Given a scenario, use appropriate networking tools.}
\label{sec:org11f66b5}

\subsection*{Crimper}
\label{sec:org4f210f2}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-CableCrimper.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A cable crimper}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Used to attach connector to end of data wire, whether coaxial, twisted pair, fiber
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Cable stripper}
\label{sec:orga009e31}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-CableStripper.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A cable stripper}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Used to remove insulation from wire / cable
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Multimeter}
\label{sec:org08ce06f}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-multimeter.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A multimeter}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Used to measure different aspects of electrical current - voltage, amps, resistance
\item Can even use it to trace wires, like a poor man's cable tester
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Tone generator and probe}
\label{sec:org85c6e57}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-toneGenerator.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Tone generator and probe}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Used to trace cables, find out where they end up
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Cable tester}
\label{sec:org12823c6}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-cableTester.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A cable tester}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Used to test the integrity of cables
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Loopback plug}
\label{sec:orgc6138a4}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-loopbackPlug.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A loopback plug}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Quick way to test a physical port (versions for ethernet, fiber)
\item Fools your machine into thinking that it is talking to someone else
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Punchdown tool}
\label{sec:org7ee2425}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-punchdownTool.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A punchdown tool}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Used to ``punch'' a wire into a wiring block
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{WiFi analyzer}
\label{sec:org55ef9db}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/2-8-wifiAnalyzer.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A WiFi analyzer's output}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item As app on smartphone or other device
\item Very useful for seeing if there are other wireless networks which might interfere with each other
\item Can guide decisions concerning channels to assign and strength of signal
\end{itemize}

\section*{3.1 – Explain basic cable types, features, and their purposes.}
\label{sec:org4084a8e}

\subsection*{Network cables}
\label{sec:org61d3e55}

\subsubsection*{Ethernet}
\label{sec:orgeabd817}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-copperCableCategories.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Twisted pair copper cabling
\begin{itemize}
\item Two wires with equal and opposite signals
\item Minimizes interference between the electrical signals of the wires
\end{itemize}
\item Unshielded twisted pair (UTP)
\begin{itemize}
\item Most common type
\item No additional shielding
\end{itemize}
\item Shielded twisted pair (STP)
\begin{itemize}
\item Additional shielding with:
\begin{itemize}
\item thick copper braided shield, makes them less flexible \& more expensive
\item foil shield - flexible but prone to tearing
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\paragraph*{Comparison of STP and UTP}
\label{sec:org836c285}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-UTP-STP.png}
\captionof{figure}{UTP and STP}
\end{center}
\paragraph*{Plenum}
\label{sec:org492c3f1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Fire-rated cable jacket, as opposed to traditional PVC
\item ``Plenum space'' - structural space in structure for air flow
\item Low-smoke materials
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{T568A and T568B terminations}
\label{sec:orgf002a1b}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth]{./images/3-1-copperCableTermination.png}
\captionof{figure}{Cable terminations}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Different pin assignments - both ends need same termination
\item Often based on tradition more than anything else
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Fiber}
\label{sec:orgc3513e4}
\begin{itemize}
\item Transmission by light
\begin{itemize}
\item Cannot monitor or tap
\item Immune to radio interference
\item Transmission over long distances
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-fiberOptic.png}
\captionof{figure}{Fiber optic cable dissection}
\end{center}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-multiModeVsSingleMode.png}
\captionof{figure}{Multi-mode and Single-mode Fiber}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Coaxial}
\label{sec:org92d1656}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-coaxialCable.png}
\captionof{figure}{Coaxial cable}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{Speed and transmission limitations}
\label{sec:org1fc6eb3}
\begin{itemize}
\item RG-6 - Television and digital cable
\begin{itemize}
\item high-speed internet over cable
\end{itemize}
\item RG-59 - Patch cables
\begin{itemize}
\item Shorter distances
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Video cables}
\label{sec:org2010a7e}

\subsubsection*{VGA}
\label{sec:orga64e8f3}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-videoCables.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item \texttt{VGA}: Video Graphics Array
\item Blue
\item Analog
\item Image degrades after 5 to 10 meters
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{HDMI}
\label{sec:org6d90646}
\begin{itemize}
\item High-Definition Multimedia Interface
\begin{itemize}
\item Video and audio stream
\item All digital
\item Proprietary
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Mini-HDMI}
\label{sec:org029fdfc}
\begin{itemize}
\item Designed for smaller devices
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DisplayPort}
\label{sec:orgb0f0707}
\begin{itemize}
\item Data sent in packetized form
\item non-proprietary
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DVI}
\label{sec:orgda6f7ba}
\begin{itemize}
\item Digital Visual Interface
\item Single or Dual link
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DVI-A}
\label{sec:org34c6e95}
\begin{itemize}
\item Analog signals only
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DVI-D / DVI-I}
\label{sec:orgcbac6a8}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{DVI-D}: Digital signals only
\item \textbf{DVI-I}: Integrated, both digital and analog
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-DVI.png}
\captionof{figure}{DVI terminations}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Multipurpose cables}
\label{sec:orgd1038e1}

\subsubsection*{Lightning}
\label{sec:orgd8604aa}
\begin{itemize}
\item Proprietary Apple cable
\item 8 pin, symmetrical, durable
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-1-lightning-connector.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Lightning connector}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{Thunderbolt}
\label{sec:org20fbeba}
\begin{itemize}
\item High speed serial connector
\item Data and power on the same cable
\item Thunderbolt v3 - 40 Gb/s, USB-C connector
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-1-thunderbolt02.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Thunderbolt connector}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{USB}
\label{sec:org9124d8d}
\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{USB Speeds}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lll}
USB Version & Name & Data Transfer Rate\\
\hline
USB 2.0 & High-Speed & 480 Mbps\\
USB 3.0 & SuperSpeed & 5 Gbps\\
USB 3.1 & SuperSpeed+ & 10Gbps\\
USB 3.2 (USB-C) & SuperSpeed+ & 10/20 Gbps\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\begin{itemize}
\item Designed to simplify connections between devices
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{USB 2.0}
\label{sec:org3f91a16}
\begin{itemize}
\item Still using USB-A connection
\item 480 Mbps
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{USB 3.0, 3.1, 3.2}
\label{sec:org5b93dec}
\begin{itemize}
\item 3.1 released 2013, 10Gbps
\item 3.2 released 2017, 10 or 20 Gbps
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{USB-C}
\label{sec:org5c8388f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Most recent connection type, designed to replace all prior USB connections
\item USB-C connection does not always mean USB 3.2 speed
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{USB terminations}
\label{sec:org2a17a24}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-1-USBterminations.png}
\captionof{figure}{USB 1.0 / 2.0 terminations}
\end{center}

