\section*{3.3 – Given a scenario, install RAM types.}
\label{sec:org7d32e53}

\subsection*{RAM types}
\label{sec:org8ec59ab}

\subsubsection*{Overview of memory terms}
\label{sec:orgf989c5f}
\begin{itemize}
\item RAM is for temporary, fast storage of data
\begin{itemize}
\item It can be thought of as the working memory of the computer.
\item Not to be confused with long-term storage such as HDDs or SDDs
\item Insufficient or underperforming RAM can be a bottleneck in the performance of the computer
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Desktop RAM: Dual-inline memory modules (DIMMs)
\item Laptop RAM: Small outline DIMMs (SO-DIMMs)
\item Both use Double Data Rate (DDR) technology
\item DDR doubles the data per cycle compared to older types
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{RAM numerology}
\label{sec:org06c825a}
\begin{itemize}
\item The numbers in the name of the RAM tell you about the speed:
\begin{itemize}
\item e.g. a stick of DDR2 RAM called DDR2-800 or PC2-6400:
\item 800 million transfers per second (MT/s)
\item 6400 MB/s
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{SDR vs DDR}
\label{sec:orgda3cd7f}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-3-SDRvsDDR.png}
\captionof{figure}{SDR vs DDR}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{DDR2}
\label{sec:org0abf1a4}
\begin{itemize}
\item decreased voltage compared to DDR1
\item increased speed through faster signalling, thus more pins
\item 240 pins
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{DDR3}
\label{sec:org820f6c0}
\begin{itemize}
\item lower power consumption, higher speed
\item also 240 pins but \emph{not} backwards compatible with DDR2
\item maximum 16GB per DIMM
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-3-DDR3.png}
\captionof{figure}{240-pin PC3-10600 4GB DIMM (DDR3-1333)}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{DDR4}
\label{sec:orge94f15a}
\begin{itemize}
\item faster again
\item max 64GB per DIMM
\item no backwards compatibility
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-3-DDR4.png}
\captionof{figure}{288-pin PC4-17000 4 GB DIMM (DDR4-2133)}
\end{center}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-3-installedDDR4.png}
\captionof{figure}{Installed bank of DDR4 memory modules}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{DDR pin chart}
\label{sec:org20bc472}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ll}
DDR Standard & Number of Pins\\
\hline
DDR1 & 184 pins\\
DDR2 & 240 pins\\
DDR3 & 240 pins\\
DDR4 & 288 pins\\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{How to install RAM:}
\label{sec:org312b3a4}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Full static precautions!
\item Orient the RAM properly, paying attention to notches
\item Insert RAM into slot
\item Press down with both thumbs until the ears lock
\item Test
\end{enumerate}

\begin{itemize}
\item Here's a video:
\end{itemize}

\url{https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HPcOZ\_v3eBI}

\begin{itemize}
\item This is worth watching, because it takes you through the entire process of installing RAM
\begin{itemize}
\item This is exactly the kind of thing you might need to regurgitate in a Practice-Based Question
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Single channel}
\label{sec:orgcd5a083}
\begin{itemize}
\item Original RAM architecture.
\begin{itemize}
\item One 64-bit address bus
\item Each stick of RAM must share this channel
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Dual channel}
\label{sec:org0c56aec}
\begin{itemize}
\item Doubles data throughput
\begin{itemize}
\item Two separate 64-bit channels, a 128-bit bus
\item Color-coded matching banks on motherboard
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Triple channel}
\label{sec:org8711c6b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Accesses three memory modules at the same time
\begin{itemize}
\item A 192-bit bus
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Quad channel}
\label{sec:orga6eb02d}
\begin{itemize}
\item Quad-channel architecture requires 4 identical memory modules placed in the correct slots
\begin{itemize}
\item Most common with DDR4
\item Four 64-bit wide buses
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-3-quad-channel-slots.png}
\captionof{figure}{Quad-channel slots on a motherboard}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Parity vs. Non-parity}
\label{sec:orga9f44bc}
\begin{itemize}
\item A ``parity check'' is a data validation technique
\item Extra bit is stored to check previous bits (thus 9 bits for every byte)
\begin{itemize}
\item Important for applications that require data integrity such as servers or workstations
\item more expensive, slightly slower
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Error correcting}
\label{sec:org549992b}
\begin{itemize}
\item ECC (Error Correction Code) detects \emph{and} corrects errors
\begin{itemize}
\item Slowest and most expensive
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{A last word about RAM}
\label{sec:org5a96161}
\begin{itemize}
\item The main thing to remember is that RAM must be \emph{compatible} with the motherboard
\begin{itemize}
\item And the best way to determine this is to go through your motherboard manual to see the compatible types of RAM
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\section*{3.4 – Select, install and configure storage devices.}
\label{sec:org4508545}
Here, we will focus on the following:

\begin{itemize}
\item Optical drives
\item Solid state devices (SSDs)
\item Magnetic hard drives (HDDs)
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Hybrid drives
\item Flash drives
\item RAID
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Optical drives}
\label{sec:orgc095eed}
\begin{itemize}
\item Data storage format: tiny bumps read by a laser beam
\begin{itemize}
\item Microscopic binary storage
\end{itemize}
\item Three main types:
\begin{itemize}
\item Compact discs (CDs)
\item Digital versatile discs (DVDs)
\item Blu-ray discs
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{CD-ROM/CD-RW}
\label{sec:org3f178d6}
\begin{itemize}
\item CD-ROM: Read-only-memory
\item CD-RW: Re-Writable
\item Speeds: multiples of 150 KB/s
\begin{itemize}
\item for example, 48x
\item 48x = 48 * 150 KB = 7.2 MB/s
\end{itemize}
\item Typical capacity: 700 MB
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
Technology & Full name & Max recording speed\\
\hline
CD-R & CD-Recordable & 48x (7.2 MB/s) or 52x (7.8 MB/s\\
CD-RW & CD-ReWritable & 24x (3.6 MB/s or 32x (4.8 MB/s)\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item A humble paperclip will dislodge a jammed optical tray!
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{DVD-ROM/DVD-RW/DVD-RW DL}
\label{sec:org97f3d23}
\begin{itemize}
\item Greater data capacity than CD-ROMs
\item Many more variations
\end{itemize}

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Comparison of DVD Technologies}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{lrrl}
DVD-ROM Technology & Sides & Total Layers & Capacity\\
\hline
DVD-5 & 1 & 1 & 4.7 GB\\
DVD-9 & 1 & 2 & 8.5 GB\\
DVD-10 & 2 & 2 & 9.4 GB\\
DVD-14 & 2 & 3 & 13.2 GB\\
DVD-18 & 2 & 4 & 17 GB\\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\begin{itemize}
\item For exam - know capacities of the most common DVD types: DVD-5 and DVD-18
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Blu-ray}
\label{sec:org30ca1f2}
\begin{itemize}
\item 25 GB for single-layer
\item 50 GB for dual-layer
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Solid-state drives}
\label{sec:org58380f7}
\begin{itemize}
\item Non-volatile memory
\item No moving parts, extremely fast
\item normally 2.5 inches
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{/Users/nick/org/comptia/sessionOne/images/3-4-SSD.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Hewlett-Packard SSD}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{AHCI vs NVMe}
\label{sec:org23bd9d5}
\begin{itemize}
\item SATA was designed for hard drives, and uses AHCI (Advanced Host Controller Interface) to move data to RAM
\item SATA revision 3 up to 600 MB/s
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{NVME}
\label{sec:orga2709e1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Non-Volatile Memory Express
\item Lower latency
\item Can use M.2 interface
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{M.2 drives}
\label{sec:org016b0da}
\begin{itemize}
\item Smaller form factor slot for SSDs
\item Can have up to 4 GB/s throughput
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-4-M2drive.png}
\captionof{figure}{M.2 drive}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Magnetic hard drives}
\label{sec:org728fea1}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-4-magneticDrive.png}
\captionof{figure}{Magnetic drive components, speeds}
\end{center}
\paragraph*{Magnetic hard drive sizes}
\label{sec:org55932ca}
\begin{itemize}
\item 2.5 inches
\item 3.5 inches
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Hybrid drives}
\label{sec:orge6d2627}
\begin{itemize}
\item Combination of HDD and SSD
\begin{itemize}
\item Spinning drive and SSD in same device
\end{itemize}
\item SSD caches the slower spinning hard drive data
\begin{itemize}
\item Increases speed - not as fast as a pure SSD, but cheaper than SSD
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/3-4-HybridDrive.png}
\captionof{figure}{Hybrid drive}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Flash}
\label{sec:orgc35dcc8}
\begin{itemize}
\item NAND-based flash memory
\item EEPROM (Electrically erasable programmable read-only memory)
\item Blocks can only be written to a finite number of times before failures start to occur
\begin{itemize}
\item \textasciitilde{} 1 million write / erase cycles, or 10 years of use (estimated by manufacturers!)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{USB flash drives}
\label{sec:org8bea24b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Standard external drive, very handy and convenient
\item but not small enough for many applications!
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Smaller flash drives}
\label{sec:org2857317}
\begin{itemize}
\item Micro-SD
\item Mini-SD
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-4-variousSDcards.png}
\captionof{figure}{Various SD cards}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Configurations}
\label{sec:org2ccc134}

\subsubsection*{RAID 0,1,5,10}
\label{sec:org7fcd0d3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Redundant Array of Independent Disks (RAID)
\begin{itemize}
\item Designed to increase the speed of reading and writing data, or
\item Create fault-tolerant volumes, or
\item Both
\end{itemize}
\item For exam, know RAID 0, 1, 5, and 10
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Setting up RAID}
\label{sec:org5a06e0f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Two or more hard drives
\item Software or hardware-based
\begin{itemize}
\item Hardware is faster:
\begin{itemize}
\item Need built-in RAID support on motherboard, or
\item RAID adapter card, or
\item External device such as Network-Attached Storage (NAS)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{RAID 0}
\label{sec:orgb3f4de3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Striping
\item High performance, data read and written quickly
\item No redundancy!
\item One failure away from breaking everything
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{RAID 1}
\label{sec:org0b5d3d5}
\begin{itemize}
\item Mirroring
\item File blocks are duplicated between two or more drives
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{RAID 5}
\label{sec:org37e9a86}
\begin{itemize}
\item Striping with parity
\item Requires at least 3 disks
\item File blocks are striped
\item High redundancy, but possibly slower performance
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{RAID 10}
\label{sec:org98cb35d}
\begin{itemize}
\item A stripe of mirrors
\item Speed of striping, redundancy of mirroring
\item Need at least 4 drives
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{A Diagram of RAID}
\label{sec:orgaa2867d}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-4-RAIDdiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{RAID diagram}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{``Hot swappable''}
\label{sec:org4936841}
\begin{itemize}
\item can add and remove while the system is running
\item (except for RAID 0)
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Fault tolerance is not backup!}
\label{sec:org48aff2b}
\begin{itemize}
\item It really isn't, don't get fooled
\item Two RAID drives can fail at the same time, destroying the whole thing.
\end{itemize}

\section*{3.5 – Given a scenario, install and configure motherboards, CPUs, and add-on cards.}
\label{sec:orga87f9ff}

\subsection*{Motherboard form factor}
\label{sec:org44b6c43}

\subsubsection*{ATX}
\label{sec:orgab97157}
\begin{itemize}
\item Advanced Technology Extended
\item Since 1995
\item Power:
\begin{itemize}
\item 20 pin connector
\item 24 pin connector + additional 4/8 pin connector
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{mATX}
\label{sec:org6f7d439}
\begin{itemize}
\item microATX
\item Smaller than ATX
\item Limited expansion slots
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{ITX}
\label{sec:orgf8a8c53}
\begin{itemize}
\item Low power motherboards
\item Since 2001
\item Mini-ITX - small form factor
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.95\textwidth]{./images/3-5-smallITX.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Mini-ITX and smaller}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Motherboard connector types}
\label{sec:org2244886}
\subsubsection*{PCI}
\label{sec:org5914bef}
\begin{itemize}
\item Peripheral Component Interconnect - 1994
\item Expansion interface
\item 32 bit or 64 bit bus widths
\item For attaching additional hardware devices to the motherboard
\begin{itemize}
\item Network cards, audio cards, USB
\item Superseded by PCIe
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.85\textwidth]{./images/3-5-PCIslots.png}
\captionof{figure}{PCI slots in motherboard}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{PCIe}
\label{sec:orgab22797}
\begin{itemize}
\item PCI Express
\item Replaced PCI and others
\begin{itemize}
\item (PCI, PCI-X, AGP)
\end{itemize}
\item Communicates serially
\begin{itemize}
\item Unidirectional serial ``lanes''
\item Slower devices don't slow down other devices
\end{itemize}
\item One, two, four, eight, sixteen, or thirty-two full duplex lanes
\begin{itemize}
\item x1, x2, x4, x8, x16, x32
\item ``x'' pronounced ``by''
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{PCIe throughput}
\label{sec:org1a33eb9}
\begin{itemize}
\item per-lane throughput:
\begin{itemize}
\item v1.x: 250 MB/s
\item v2.x: 500 MB/s
\item v3.0: \textasciitilde{}1 GB/s
\item v4.0: \textasciitilde{}2 GB/s
\item v5.0: \textasciitilde{}4 GB/s
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Riser card}
\label{sec:org328434a}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-5-riserCard.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Riser card in IBM PS/2}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Allows installation of additional expansion cards
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Socket types}
\label{sec:org930147e}
\begin{itemize}
\item Different CPUs have different socket requirements
\item And these are very specific - CPUs often not upgrade-able because of this
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-5-CPUsockets.png}
\captionof{figure}{CPU socket types}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Zero Insertion Force (ZIF) - Pins on CPU, delicately dropped into sockets
\item Pin Grid Array (PGA) - pins are on CPU
\item Land Grid Array (LGA) - pins are on motherboard
\begin{itemize}
\item easier to damage the motherboard
\end{itemize}
\item In all sockets, CPU needs to be aligned correctly - often there are visual cues on the CPU itself
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Front panel connector}
\label{sec:org655f80b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Connections from motherboard to various ports on the front or sides of case
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Internal USB connector}
\label{sec:orga6c7fbc}
\begin{itemize}
\item From USB on motherboard
\item to external USB ports for mouse, keyboard, external storage, etc
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{BIOS/UEFI settings}
\label{sec:orga8a24b1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Basic Input / Output System
\begin{itemize}
\item The software that starts the computer
\begin{itemize}
\item firmware
\item System BIOS
\item ROM / flash memory
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Launching BIOS}
\label{sec:org700fd89}
\begin{itemize}
\item Pressing specific keys / combinations during startup
\begin{itemize}
\item Del, F1, F2, Ctrl-S, or Ctrl-Alt-S, for example
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Windows 8 and Windows 10}
\label{sec:org39a1b8b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Fast Startup is too quick to open BIOS
\item Must disable Fast Startup first (Control Panel --> Power Options)
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Legacy BIOS}
\label{sec:org8afc585}
\begin{itemize}
\item Original BIOS, 25-30 years old
\item Limited hardware support
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{UEFI BIOS}
\label{sec:orgaa02b41}
\begin{itemize}
\item Unified Extensible Firmware Interface
\item Replaced traditional BIOS
\item Graphical \textbf{or} text-based
\item Advantages:
\begin{itemize}
\item Can boot from larger (>2.2 TB) partition
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{BIOS simulators:}
\label{sec:org0ca3579}
\begin{itemize}
\item Legacy Phoenix BIOS:
\begin{itemize}
\item \url{https://geekprank.com/bios/}
\end{itemize}
\item Lenovo BIOS simulator:
\begin{itemize}
\item \url{https://download.lenovo.com/bsco/index.html}
\begin{itemize}
\item Choose one of the ThinkPad X1 models - can choose between graphical or text
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Boot options}
\label{sec:org4ee05e9}
\begin{itemize}
\item Can choose which drive to boot from
\begin{itemize}
\item Which hard drive, or CD-ROM / DVD, USB, others
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Firmware updates}
\label{sec:org44a602f}
\begin{itemize}
\item BIOS needs to be updated
\item Should be first thing you check when you start up a new computer
\item Sometimes will need to be updated to support a new device
\item Always make a backup of your BIOS before flashing!
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Security settings}
\label{sec:orga7915bb}
\paragraph*{BIOS Passwords}
\label{sec:org34c2a1e}
\begin{itemize}
\item User password
\begin{itemize}
\item Need password to start the system
\end{itemize}
\item Supervisor password
\begin{itemize}
\item Restricts BIOS changes
\item Need supervisor password to make changes
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{Full disk Encryption}
\label{sec:org59df760}
\begin{itemize}
\item Encrypt \textbf{everything}
\item Windows BitLocker disk encryption
\begin{itemize}
\item BIOS integrates with TPM
\item TPM - Trusted Platform Module
\begin{itemize}
\item not on all motherboards
\item Adds advanced encryption functions
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\paragraph*{Secure Boot}
\label{sec:org63836fe}
\begin{itemize}
\item Part of the UEFI specification
\item Only allows digitally signed software to run
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{CMOS battery}
\label{sec:orgeccae83}
\begin{itemize}
\item In the olden days, user BIOS settings were stored in:
\begin{itemize}
\item A Complementary Metal-Oxide Semiconductor
\begin{itemize}
\item which is a type of memory that needed power to retain data
\end{itemize}
\item Would have a battery, could be removed to reset BIOS settings
\end{itemize}
\item These days, stored in flash memory - move a jumper to reset
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{CPU features}
\label{sec:org281c23e}

\subsubsection*{Single core CPU}
\label{sec:org02b6292}
\begin{itemize}
\item Back when a CPU was just its own thing, one unit
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Hyperthreading}
\label{sec:orgb8db4b6}
\begin{itemize}
\item Next step: 
\begin{itemize}
\item A single CPU can accept and process two or more sets of instructions simultaneously
\item OS sees more than one CPU
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Multicore}
\label{sec:org64cc9f7}
\begin{itemize}
\item Dual-core, quad-core, etc
\item Each core can have its own cache or can share cache with other cores
\item Multicore CPUs usually have hyperthreading as well
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{CPU cache}
\label{sec:org8d5a9be}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-5-CPUcache.png}
\captionof{figure}{Cache memory}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item The CPU caches memory in storage local to chip
\item Static RAM (SRAM) - much faster and more expensive than dynamic RAM
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item L1 cache - inside the CPU
\item L2 - built onto or next to CPU
\item L3 - shared by different cores
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/3-5-CPUcacheDiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{CPU diagram}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Virtual technology}
\label{sec:org1d7347c}
\begin{itemize}
\item Support for virtualization is in the CPU
\item If virtualization is not supported by CPU, then you will not be able to run virtual machines on this computer, sorry!
\item Can be enabled in BIOS
\begin{itemize}
\item Intel Virtualization Technology (VT)
\item AMD Virtualization (AMD-V)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Speeds}
\label{sec:orgb8930e4}
\begin{itemize}
\item ``Clock speed'' of CPU
\begin{itemize}
\item Megahertz (MHz) or gigahertz (GHz)
\end{itemize}
\item Actual speed is a combination of many factors
\begin{itemize}
\item Bus architecture, CPU memory cache sizes, operating system
\item Don't see CPUs being marketed with GHz any more
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Overclocking}
\label{sec:org6f656b3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Can increase the clock speed of a CPU past its recommended value
\begin{itemize}
\item Produces more heat, CPU can become unstable
\item Or even break, bringing more of your system down with it
\item Will generally void your warranty!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Integrated GPU}
\label{sec:org7a076cf}
\begin{itemize}
\item Graphics require additional calculation and processing
\item In the olden days this was always done by a separate component
\item Now the Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) is usually integrated into the CPU
\item In desktops and some laptops, can add additional graphics card to do this.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Compatibility of different CPUs}
\label{sec:orga625460}

\subsubsection*{Intel vs AMD}
\label{sec:org76fd0c1}
\begin{itemize}
\item American Micro Devices, usually a little cheaper
\item Intel usually seen as having better performance
\item But both broadly equivalent
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Cooling mechanism}
\label{sec:org80eaba2}

\subsubsection*{Fans}
\label{sec:org698be65}
\begin{itemize}
\item Cases have fans to pull and push air
\item Airflow can be impeded by components
\item Location of cables
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/3-5-cabinet-airflow-diagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{Cabinet airflow diagram}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{Heat sink}
\label{sec:org2ff990e}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-5-cpuHeatsinkThermalPasteDiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{CPU, heatsink, and thermal paste}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item Sits on chip, dissipates heat through conduction
\item Thermal compound (paste) between
\item Problems with heat sink or thermal paste can cause heating problems
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-5-CPUheatsinkFan.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{CPU, heatsink, and fan (thermal paste between CPU and heatsink)}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Liquid}
\label{sec:org88aaf56}
\begin{itemize}
\item Coolant circulated through computer
\begin{itemize}
\item Potential points of failure:
\begin{itemize}
\item Pump can fail
\item Air can get in fluid lines
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item Water and other liquids conduct heat better than air
\item For high end systems or hobbyists and serious nerds
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-5-liquidCooling.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Liquid cooling}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Expansion cards}
\label{sec:org95a08e4}
\begin{itemize}
\item An ``expansion card'' is a printed circuit board that plugs into a computer's motherboard
\begin{itemize}
\item Enhances its function in some way
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/3-5-VideoCard.png}
\captionof{figure}{An extremely fancy ATI video card}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{Video cards, aka Graphical Processing Units (GPU)}
\label{sec:orgd608403}
\begin{itemize}
\item Works independently do the math for generating images
\begin{itemize}
\item Takes burden off the CPU
\end{itemize}
\item In lower-end machines, can be in CPU - ``on-die''
\begin{itemize}
\item So-called ``integrated GPUs'' not as powerful
\item or Video expansion card:
\begin{itemize}
\item Uses more power, takes up room, can add heat
\item But allows the off-loading of graphics calculations from the CPU and thus production of superior graphics
\item Important if doing computer-aided design (CAD) or playing super-fancy video games
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Sound cards}
\label{sec:org0b7b19c}
\begin{itemize}
\item Rarely seen Not seen as much these days, unless doing high-end audio work
\item Usually integrated into motherboard, and generally adequate
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{eSATA card}
\label{sec:org60be740}
\begin{itemize}
\item Needed if eSATA will be used
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Reminder} External Serial Advanced Technology Attachment or eSATA is an external interface for SATA technologies
\item Often faster than USB for connecting to external storage devices
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{3.7 – Summarize power supply types and features.}
\label{sec:orgeea5a23}
\subsection*{Power Supply Unit (PSU)}
\label{sec:org4cf0c0c}
\begin{itemize}
\item For both desktops and laptops, main job is to convert alternating current (AC) from the power socket in the wall to direct current (DC) for use by the computer
\begin{itemize}
\item In a desktop, the PSU is inside the case
\item In a laptop, it is usually external and we sometimes call it a ``power brick''
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Destop power supply unit}
\label{sec:org24fa9e8}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-7-DesktopPSU.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Desktop PSU}
\end{center}
(notice the red switch which converts the voltage input)

\subsubsection*{Laptop power supply}
\label{sec:org194ad7c}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-7-LaptopPowerBrick.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Laptop power brick}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item The ``brick'' is what converts AC to DC, with the leads going to the wall power socket and the laptop power socket visible
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Input 115V vs. 220V}
\label{sec:org806ff43}
\begin{itemize}
\item US is 110-120V, most of the rest of the world is 220-240V
\item Most of the time this can be handled automatically by the power supply
\item But not always - sometimes a switch on the back (see picture of desktop PSU)
\item Look at inscription on power brick to make sure
\begin{itemize}
\item if it says ``INPUT: 100-240V, 50/60 Hz'' then it can be used in either 115V or 220V power settings without additional work
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Laptop power brick label}
\label{sec:org68cf9ba}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/3-7-PowerBrickLabel.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Laptop power supply label}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Output 5.5V vs. 12V}
\label{sec:org01ffed2}
\begin{itemize}
\item Power supply converts AC to DC
\item Converts to 3.3V DC, 5.5V DC, and 12V DC
\item All voltages used by different parts of the computer
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Ampere, Voltage, Power}
\label{sec:orgf4e0f08}
\begin{itemize}
\item Ampere: amp, A - rate of electron flow
\begin{itemize}
\item Can be thought of as the ``diameter of the hose''
\end{itemize}
\item Voltage: volt, V - Electrical ``pressure'' pushing electrons
\item Power: usually measured in watts (W)
\begin{itemize}
\item volts * amps = watts
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Current}
\label{sec:org9c7efad}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Alternating Current (AC)
\begin{itemize}
\item Direction of current constantly reverses
\item Better at transmitting over long distances
\end{itemize}
\item Direct Current (DC)
\begin{itemize}
\item One direction, constant voltage
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/3-7-ACvsDC.png}
\captionof{figure}{AC vs DC}
\end{center}

\subsection*{24-pin motherboard adapter}
\label{sec:orgd60ce23}
\begin{itemize}
\item Main motherboard power for ATX motherboards
\end{itemize}
\begin{figure}[h]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.15\textwidth]{./images/3-7-24-pin-motherboard-power-connector.png}
\caption{24-pin motherboard power connector}
\end{figure}

\subsection*{Power supply output}
\label{sec:org7bd9ebb}
\begin{itemize}
\item +12 V
\begin{itemize}
\item PCIe adapters, hard drives, fans, others
\end{itemize}
\item +5 V 
\begin{itemize}
\item Some motherboard components, not as many these days
\end{itemize}
\item +3.3 V
\begin{itemize}
\item M.2 slots, RAM, logic circuits
\end{itemize}
\item -12 V Integrated LAN
\begin{itemize}
\item some PCI cards
\end{itemize}
\item -5 V now rarely used
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Here's what a set of power supply output wires looks like:}
\label{sec:org0d2c658}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/3-7-PowerSupplyOutput.png}
\captionof{figure}{Power supply output, labelled}
\end{center}
\subsection*{Number of devices/types of devices to be powered}
\label{sec:orgd7ea972}
\begin{itemize}
\item When thinking about the Power Supply Unit (PSU) required for a device,
\begin{itemize}
\item Judge power supply needed by number of components to be powered
\item Video cards will be biggest draw
\item Generally, add 50\% capacity so that things can be added in future
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{3.8 – Given a scenario, select and configure appropriate components for a custom PC}
\label{sec:orgfb79a10}

\subsection*{Graphic/CAD/CAM design workstation}
\label{sec:org61fd3ec}
\begin{itemize}
\item CAD = Computer Aided Design
\item CAM = Computer Aided Manufacturing
\end{itemize}
\emph{These computers will need:}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Multicore processor}
\begin{itemize}
\item multiple tasks and calculations being performed
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{High-end video}
\begin{itemize}
\item complex graphics
\item dedicated video card
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Maximum RAM}
\begin{itemize}
\item again, due to the many calculations being performed
\item significant memory use as a result
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{SSD}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{high speed storage}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Audio-video editing workstation}
\label{sec:org2c08b20}
\begin{itemize}
\item These computers will likely need:
\item Specialized audio and video card
\begin{itemize}
\item High quality audio
\item High quality sound
\end{itemize}
\item Large, fast hard drive
\begin{itemize}
\item Constant disk writes
\item SSD for speed
\end{itemize}
\item Dual monitors
\begin{itemize}
\item Edit in one monitor, view output in the other
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Virtualization workstation}
\label{sec:org9672add}
\begin{itemize}
\item Will be running numerous virtual machines
\begin{itemize}
\item This will require significant RAM
\begin{itemize}
\item and as many CPU cores as you can cram in there
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\item \textbf{Maximum RAM and CPU cores}
\begin{itemize}
\item Each virtual device will need its own memory
\item Maximum CPU cores due to constant processing
\item Virtualization apps use multiple cores
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Gaming PC}
\label{sec:orgfb91519}
Needs:
\begin{itemize}
\item Multicore processor
\begin{itemize}
\item Again, due to the multiple tasks being performed
\end{itemize}
\item High-end video/specialized GPU
\begin{itemize}
\item Graphically complex tasks
\end{itemize}
\item High-definition sound card
\begin{itemize}
\item For the full experience
\end{itemize}
\item High-end cooling
\begin{itemize}
\item All components will be running very hot
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Standard ``thick client''}
\label{sec:org481b825}
\begin{itemize}
\item Your standard computer
\item ``Thick'' only relative to ``thin'' client
\begin{itemize}
\item Desktop applications
\item Programs stored on hard drive
\item Applications run locally with CPU and RAM
\end{itemize}
\item Make sure it meets recommended requirements for selected OS
\begin{itemize}
\item This will include CPU, RAM, disk space
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Thin client}
\label{sec:org5e9aec3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Most things run on a remote server
\begin{itemize}
\item Basic applications
\item Only a virtual desktop infrastructure (VDI)
\end{itemize}
\item Make sure it meets minimum requirements for selected OS
\begin{itemize}
\item and only a minimal OS required
\end{itemize}
\item Network connectivity
\begin{itemize}
\item Without network connectivity, will not work
\item Everything important happens remotely
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Network Attached Storage device (NAS)}
\label{sec:org387df38}
\begin{itemize}
\item Dedicated storage attached to network
\item Can be used for: 
\begin{itemize}
\item Media streaming
\begin{itemize}
\item to sites local and remote
\end{itemize}
\item File sharing
\begin{itemize}
\item Easy access to shred resources
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item Best with a Gigabit NIC
\begin{itemize}
\item Fastest most reliable network access necessary
\end{itemize}
\item You would want it to have a RAID array
\begin{itemize}
\item This device is all about holding data and keeping it safe
\end{itemize}
\item ``Multiply redundant'' - Different servers duplicating its work
\end{itemize}
\section*{3.9 – Given a scenario, install and configure common devices.}
\label{sec:org2c64c3d}

\subsection*{Desktop}
\label{sec:org881d0d8}

\subsubsection*{Desktop thin client}
\label{sec:orgf849d65}
\begin{itemize}
\item The kind of computer that might be used as a POS (Point of Sale) device, or at a reception desk
\begin{itemize}
\item Not intended for serious computational work, but for simply running applications that can be remote from the actual terminal
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-9-ThinClent.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{HP t630 Thin Client}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Very little configuration
\item Mouse, monitor, keyboard
\item Inexpensive to buy, easy to replace
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Desktop thick client}
\label{sec:org00f1b48}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-9-ThickClientDesktop.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Thick client (desktop)}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Traditional computer setup
\item With traditional requirements:
\begin{itemize}
\item Operating system
\item Device drivers
\item Applications
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Account setup/settings for thin and thick clients}
\label{sec:orgbd11d0f}
\begin{itemize}
\item Centralized account management
\begin{itemize}
\item Microsoft Active Directory
\end{itemize}
\item Thin client: No local permissions needed - all on network
\item Thick client: Added to Microsoft domain
\end{itemize}

\section*{3.10 – Given a scenario, configure SOHO multifunction devices/printers and settings.}
\label{sec:orgbea4008}

\subsection*{Use appropriate drivers for a given operating system}
\label{sec:org990557b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Specific drivers for specific model
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Configuration settings}
\label{sec:orgce7d623}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Duplex}
\begin{itemize}
\item Prints on both sides of paper
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Collate}
\begin{itemize}
\item Multiple copies in their proper order
\end{itemize}
\item Orientation
\item Portrait vs landscape
\item Quality
\begin{itemize}
\item Resolution, color, greyscale
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Device sharing}
\label{sec:org76f3e6e}

\subsubsection*{Wired}
\label{sec:orgbf097c7}
\begin{itemize}
\item USB
\item Serial
\item Ethernet
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Wireless}
\label{sec:org9e95a0b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Bluetooth
\item 802.11 (a,b,g,n,ac)
\item Infrastructure vs. ad hoc
\begin{itemize}
\item No access point, direct link between devices
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Integrated print service (hardware)}
\label{sec:org607e669}
\begin{itemize}
\item Print server often inside the printer - a component of the printer
\begin{itemize}
\item Sets up printing queue itself, as different devices sent print jobs to it
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Cloud printing/remote printing}
\label{sec:orged82bba}
\begin{itemize}
\item Google and HP, among others, offer cloud printing services
\begin{itemize}
\item Print from anywhere in the world to a specific printer
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Public/shared devices}
\label{sec:org33bdb2b}

\subsubsection*{Sharing local/networked device via operating system settings}
\label{sec:orgc454117}
\begin{itemize}
\item A printer attached to one computer can be shared with other computers on the network
\begin{itemize}
\item Windows: Settings --> Devices --> Printers and scanners. Then ``Printer Properties'' ``Sharing'' tab
\item Apple / Mac OS: System Preferences --> Printers \& Scanners.  Click ``share this printer on the network''
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\paragraph*{TCP/Bonjour/Airprint}
\label{sec:org0d38069}
\begin{itemize}
\item Allows standalone printer to be shared with devices on the same LAN
\begin{itemize}
\item Bonjour and Airprint both proprietary Apple protocols
\item TCP is the same protocol we have been learning about, a backbone protocol
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{3.11 – Given a scenario, install and maintain various print technologies.}
\label{sec:org1d92254}

\subsection*{Laser}
\label{sec:orgdf1366a}

\subsubsection*{Laser printer parts}
\label{sec:orgdfa9e09}

\begin{itemize}
\item Imaging drum
\item fuser assembly
\item transfer belt
\item transfer roller
\item pickup rollers
\item separation pads
\item duplexing assembly (allows double-sided printing)
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Imaging process: processing, charging, exposing, developing, transferring, fusing, and cleaning}
\label{sec:orgde2cf0b}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-11-LaserPrinterDiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{Laser printer components}
\end{center}
\subsubsection*{Laser printer maintenance}
\label{sec:orgd9874c9}
\begin{itemize}
\item Replace toner
\item Apply maintenance kit
\item Calibrate
\item Clean
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Inkjet}
\label{sec:org8f77b84}
\begin{itemize}
\item Inexpensive in itself, but ink is costly
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-11-InkjetPrinterInsideDiagram.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Inkjet printer components - the only terms you need to know are listed below}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Inkjet components: Ink cartridge}
\label{sec:org7f57c1c}
\begin{itemize}
\item Places drops of ink on the page
\begin{itemize}
\item Pulled from cartridge
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Inkjet components: Print head}
\label{sec:org30a7630}
\begin{itemize}
\item Often the print head is integrated into the cartridge
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Inkjet components: Feed rollers}
\label{sec:org8a3545d}
\begin{itemize}
\item Pick up and feed paper
\begin{itemize}
\item Can wear down, get dirty
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Inkjet components: Duplexing assembly}
\label{sec:org44af4db}
\begin{itemize}
\item Not a part of every printer
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Inkjet components: Carriage and belt}
\label{sec:org167c3b5}
\begin{itemize}
\item Ink cartridges move over the paper
\item Belt moves the carriage back and forth
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Inkjet maintenance: Calibrate}
\label{sec:org0564a1c}
\begin{itemize}
\item Nozzles need to be aligned to the paper
\item Usually on-board calibration program
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Inkjet Maintenance:}
\label{sec:orga4a0ecb}
\begin{itemize}
\item Clean heads
\item Replace cartridges
\item Calibrate
\item Clear jams
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Thermal Printers}
\label{sec:orged17de8}

\begin{itemize}
\item Most often found in commerical settings, printing receipts and other smaller documents
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-11-ThermalPrinterPrintingProcess.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Thermal printer printing process}
\end{center}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-11-ThermalPrinter.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{A thermal label printer (opened)}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item Parts: 
\begin{itemize}
\item Feed assembly, heating element
\item Special thermal paper
\end{itemize}
\item Maintenance: 
\begin{itemize}
\item Replace paper
\item Clean heating element
\item Remove debris
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Impact printers}
\label{sec:orgb021e9b}
\begin{itemize}
\item The oldest, most classic printers around
\begin{itemize}
\item Dot matrix, daisy wheel
\item Usually loud and slow
\item Still used because for some print jobs they can be quite fast
\item Due to impact printing process, the only kind of printer that can use carbon paper to make multiple copies
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
\item Parts:
\begin{itemize}
\item Print head, ribbon, tractor feed
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Dot matrix printer}
\label{sec:org3fbd061}
\begin{itemize}
\item Can produce both text and graphics, though neither will look particularly good compared to laser, or even inkjet
\item Complex sets of tiny pins strike an ink-coated ribbon
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-11-DotMatrixPrinter.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Dot matrix printer}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item These have a distinctive sound, here's a YouTube clip if you've never heard the relaxing sounds of a dot matrix printer:
\begin{itemize}
\item \url{https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cDX3rVuW-7U}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection*{Daisy wheel printer}
\label{sec:org3c605b7}
\begin{itemize}
\item Almost like an automated old-fashioned typewriter
\begin{itemize}
\item Pre-formed type elements strike paper through an ink-coated ribbon, producing text
\item In fact, some manual typewriters used daisy wheel print heads
\item These days, more like a historical curiosity, though they are capable of producing good looking text
\item Text \textbf{only} - no graphics
\item So loud!  Here is a YouTube video if you want to hear how they sound:
\item \url{https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CTBM9JELUYQ}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Impact printer paper}
\label{sec:org186dbf6}
\begin{itemize}
\item Can use regular old printer paper
\item For fast, extensive dot matrix printing can use continuous sheets
\item Can use carbon copies between pages
\end{itemize}

\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/3-11-DotMatrixContinuousSheetPaper.jpg}
\captionof{figure}{Dot matrix continuous feed paper (this one has carbon copying built in!)}
\end{center}

\subsubsection*{Impact printer maintenance:}
\label{sec:orgb2c2d0b}
\begin{itemize}
\item Replace ribbon
\item replace print head
\item replace paper
\end{itemize}

\section*{4.1 – Compare and contrast cloud computing concepts.}
\label{sec:orgb3cd221}
\subsection*{Cloud computing}
\label{sec:org0699595}
\begin{itemize}
\item Services that are housed ``in the Cloud''
\begin{itemize}
\item i.e. on someone else's computer, server, or network
\item Largest providers of such services today:
\begin{itemize}
\item Google Cloud
\item Amazon (AWS)
\item Microsoft (Azure)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{``The Cloud''}
\label{sec:org687080c}
\begin{itemize}
\item What is ``The Cloud''? \emph{precisely?}
\begin{itemize}
\item As mentioned above, ``The Cloud'' is essentially a computer (or network of computers!) that belongs to someone else
\item And that someone is renting it out to you
\item The computer that you are renting can act as:
\begin{itemize}
\item a mail server
\item a file server
\item a print server
\item any other kind of server, really
\end{itemize}
\item Sometimes the ``rent'' is your personal information
\begin{itemize}
\item i.e., Gmail
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{A momentary definition of The Cloud}
\label{sec:orgfa68f6e}
\begin{quote}
The cloud is a suite of hardware and software - managed by a service provider or organization - that provides data, applications, and other resources to users. often via the Internet
\end{quote}
\begin{itemize}
\item The kinds of services provided on the cloud, and the ways we think about them, are constantly changing and quite complicated.
\item Fortunately, the A+ only requires you to know the basic stuff
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Cloud Computing}
\label{sec:org7a5bfd0}
\begin{itemize}
\item In fact, The A+ only really deals with \texttt{Cloud Computing} which has a more limited definition:
\begin{itemize}
\item ``Cloud computing is a model for enabling ubiquitous, convenient, on-demand network access to a shared pool of configurable computing resources (e.g., networks, servers, storage, applications, and services) that can be rapidly provisioned and released with minimal management effort or service provider interaction.''
\begin{itemize}
\item For the source of the above quote and the standards from which CompTIA gets all of its thinking about cloud computing, go here:
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://nvlpubs.nist.gov/nistpubs/Legacy/SP/nistspecialpublication800-145.pdf}{NIST definition of cloud computing}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{So, the key is,}
\label{sec:orgdfa4b84}
\begin{itemize}
\item from above quote - ``minimal management effort or service provider interaction.''
\item That's the nice thing about a service like Gmail - it usually works right, you don't have to worry about how to set it up
\begin{itemize}
\item And chances are you've never had to deal with Google about any aspect of it.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{This means that,}
\label{sec:org93352eb}
\begin{itemize}
\item Cloud computing saves money and time
\begin{itemize}
\item You might not need to have an in-house network guy any more
\item You won't need to have a server room, sucking up electricity and generating heat and further problems
\item Someone else is responsible for maintaining your stuff
\begin{itemize}
\item Of course, the last can create its own problems\ldots{}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{\textbf{IaaS} Infrastructure as a Service}
\label{sec:orgc643300}
\begin{itemize}
\item A service that offers computer networking, storage, load balancing, routing, and VM (virtual machine) hosting
\begin{itemize}
\item The \emph{provider} hosts all the devious and complicated equipment and software required to manage such things
\item With a subscription service, you can access hardware only when you need it
\begin{itemize}
\item This model has \emph{scalability} - you can quickly ramp up the scale of the service without having to buy a bunch of new equipment
\item Common providers:
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://cloud.google.com/}{Google Cloud Computing}
\item \href{https://aws.amazon.com/}{Amazon Web Services}
\item \href{https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/}{Microsoft Azure} \footnote{This is the service I used to have a virtual Windows 10 machine in class so I could show you some things about that operating system.}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{\textbf{SaaS} Software as a Service}
\label{sec:org125216d}
\begin{itemize}
\item This is the most commonly used and recognized kind of cloud computing
\begin{itemize}
\item This allows users to access an individual application provided by a third party over the internet
\item Google is really the master of this service, with \href{http://mail.google.com}{Gmail}, \href{http://docs.google.com}{Google Docs}, etc
\item But Microsoft is catching up, with \href{https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/microsoft-365}{Office 365}
\item This means that the applications themselves do not have to be installed on your device, nor do you need to worry about updating them.
\begin{itemize}
\item As someone who has dallied with the idea of setting of their own email server, it is \emph{not easy} and I am happy to outsource that!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{\textbf{PaaS} Platform as a Service}
\label{sec:orgd717410}
\begin{itemize}
\item This one is slightly trickier for newcomers to understand
\begin{itemize}
\item Renting a fully configured environment can allow developers to work on software without having to manage that environment themselves.
\item Management, updating, keeping the data secure is all the responsibility of the provider
\item This is also where the definitions start to break down - is a virtual desktop infrastructure, software, or a platform?
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Public vs. private vs. hybrid vs. community}
\label{sec:org46b0ceb}
\begin{itemize}
\item These definitions are, again, those defined by \href{https://www.nist.gov/}{NIST}
\begin{itemize}
\item They measure how cloud resources are shared and apportioned out by providers
\item Can also determine how much they cost
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Public cloud}
\label{sec:org70d037b}
\begin{itemize}
\item The service provider offers applications and storage space to the general public over the Internet
\begin{itemize}
\item Examples include \href{https://www.nist.gov/}{Dropbox}, \href{http://mail.google.com}{Gmail}, \href{https://www.rackspace.com/}{Rackspace}, and other usual suspects
\item These services end up being much cheaper - you can rent a tiny little stripped down virtual Linux machine for as little as five dollars per \emph{year}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Private Cloud}
\label{sec:org7b5c197}
\begin{itemize}
\item Usually designed specifically for a particular organization or individual
\begin{itemize}
\item Individuals / businesses purchase their own software / hardware to run their own virtualization / cloud service
\end{itemize}
\item Often loses some of the desirable features of cloud computing
\begin{itemize}
\item Not as scaleable, you are now responsible for managing and updating software
\item BUT! Now you can control your own security, the data all stays on-site
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Shared resources}
\label{sec:org978f8f2}
\begin{itemize}
\item Much of the point of cloud computing is \emph{sharing} - of resources, cost, responsibilities
\item And, depending on the model you adapt for your cloud, sharing your data
\begin{itemize}
\item The two basic choices are \textbf{internal} or \textbf{external} cloud architecture
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Internal vs. external clouds}
\label{sec:org5df1c4c}
\begin{itemize}
\item Internal
\begin{itemize}
\item No resources (i.e. servers, bandwidth) are shared
\item You pay for all that stuff yourself
\item Also have to maintain it yourself
\item But you also control it yourself, and most of the costs are up-front
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Internal vs. external clouds, cont'd}
\label{sec:orgb9d8e07}
\begin{itemize}
\item External
\begin{itemize}
\item Resources shared with others on an external cloud
\item Infrastructure owned by someone else
\begin{itemize}
\item (Who is responsible for keeping it running)
\end{itemize}
\item Generally less expensive;
\begin{itemize}
\item Cost can be monitored over time
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Important features of cloud computing}
\label{sec:orgc1bf38a}
\begin{itemize}
\item The next few slides / sections are about various features of cloud computing
\begin{itemize}
\item Important to know, but more importantly
\begin{itemize}
\item This is what CompTIA \emph{expects} you to know:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{rapid elasticity}
\item \textbf{on-demand} service
\item \textbf{resource pooling}
\item \textbf{measured service}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Rapid elasticity}
\label{sec:org62bf588}
\begin{itemize}
\item The ability to:
\begin{itemize}
\item Build a network or resource quickly and efficiently
\begin{itemize}
\item ``Bob we just launched Widget 2.0 and we will have 2,000 more orders a month!
\begin{itemize}
\item ``No prob, I'll just spin up 500 new identical webservers by clicking this button!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item Not all providers can provide the kind of elasticity you might want
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{On-demand}
\label{sec:orgd437770}
\begin{itemize}
\item On your own, adding new software or hardware can be difficult, expensive, and time-consuming
\begin{itemize}
\item With a cloud service, it can be instant
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Resource pooling}
\label{sec:org19fee55}
\begin{itemize}
\item The provider's resources can be considered one big pool of stuff - hardware, bandwidth, software
\begin{itemize}
\item The client does not know (or care) where the stuff is
\begin{itemize}
\item They just know what they want from it
\item The provider can then divvy up its resources: memory, storage, computing power
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Measured service}
\label{sec:orgdb3b3b8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Costs and use are monitored by the provider
\begin{itemize}
\item Data provided to client
\item Allowing careful assessment and planning of costs and use of the services
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Metered vs non-metered}
\label{sec:org76908cf}
\begin{itemize}
\item Metered cost: 
\begin{itemize}
\item Everything tracked and with incremental charge
\begin{itemize}
\item Usually including things like bandwidth, storage, number of VMs
\item Part of \emph{rapid elasticity} - if you need more bandwidth, you get it quickly but pay for every byte of it
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item Non-metered cost:
\begin{itemize}
\item One charge for all services; things like bandwidth and storage are either
\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{fixed} or \emph{unlimited}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Real world examples of measured service}
\label{sec:orgbfd397e}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=85\textwidth]{./images/4-1-azureVMcosts.png}
\captionof{figure}{Azure Windows 10 VM metered cost}
\end{center}

\begin{itemize}
\item Here's my use of an Azure Windows 10 VM, the one we used in class
\begin{itemize}
\item I got charged for bandwidth, storage, having a virtual network (which I didn't; only one VM), and the number of virtual machines I used
\begin{itemize}
\item (You can see how on July 10th I realized I didn't need any storage and turned it off)
\end{itemize}
\item When my virtual machine was on, I was charged; when it was off, no charge
\begin{itemize}
\item You can see the two times I had it on for our class!
\end{itemize}
\item But don't worry about the cost, you get \$200 in credit from Microsoft when you start
\begin{itemize}
\item I did this just to learn about Azure because I had never used it before
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}
\item Compare that with the cloud server I use in real life:
\begin{itemize}
\item (which has \emph{non-metered cost})
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/4-1-myCloudServer.png}
\captionof{figure}{my cute dedicated server}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item I pay a fixed amount per month and I get: 
\begin{itemize}
\item unlimited bandwidth
\item as many VMs as I can cram on there
\begin{itemize}
\item (5 right now)
\end{itemize}
\item 1 TB storage
\end{itemize}
\item Nice deal, eh?
\begin{itemize}
\item But I get charged whether I use it or not,
\begin{itemize}
\item Whereas right now I am paying nothing for my Azure VM
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Off-site email applications}
\label{sec:org59d32b0}
\begin{itemize}
\item This is probably one of the most widely used cloud applications
\begin{itemize}
\item So normalized that you probably don't even realize you're using a cloud service
\item It is perfect for the cloud service model:
\begin{itemize}
\item Email servers are big, complicated, have huge security issues
\item Just think about all the spam and phishing that you are generally sheltered from if you use a big provider
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item Services offered by Yahoo, Google, Microsoft, \href{https://www.aol.com/}{AOL} even!
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Cloud file storage services}
\label{sec:org86c52a3}
\begin{itemize}
\item Also good for a cloud model, and one of the first cloud services ever offered
\begin{itemize}
\item Other people mange your storage and keep it safe
\item You can access it from anywhere, from any device
\item Works well for collaboration / sharing
\item Can synchronize between devices
\begin{itemize}
\item Then you will always have the most current version
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection*{Cloud storage providers}
\label{sec:org78af6d8}
\begin{itemize}
\item There is no lack of these, but here are the biggest players:
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{http://www.dropbox.com}{Dropbox}
\item \href{https://www.google.com/drive/}{Google Drive}
\item \href{http://www.icloud.com}{Apple iCloud}
\item \href{https://onedrive.live.com/}{Microsoft OneDrive}
\end{itemize}
\item Generally all these folks have a free / extremely low cost tier
\begin{itemize}
\item And then they suck you in for more
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Synchronization apps}
\label{sec:org8c6da52}
\begin{itemize}
\item Google Drive, OneCloud, and iCloud all have versions of this:
\begin{itemize}
\item An app will run on your device (workstation, smartphone, tablet)
\item The app will monitor your files and update them to the cloud when they change
\end{itemize}
\item I would feel remiss if I did not mention a great open source alternative to these:
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://syncthing.net}{Syncthing}, which can also run on your phone, computer, tablet, whatever
\item Runs on GUI or CLI
\item But it can be complicated and not for beginners!
\begin{itemize}
\item (you should take that as a challenge!)
\item (Syncthing will not be on the A+!)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Cloud-based applications}
\label{sec:org26e5318}
\begin{itemize}
\item The app lives in the cloud, not on your computer
\begin{itemize}
\item Data stored in cloud
\item As is the application itself
\item You don't have to update it or manage it
\item But your data might not be so secure\ldots{}
\end{itemize}
\item Google Docs, Microsoft Office 365 are examples
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{Cloud virtual desktops}
\label{sec:orgd040a8a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Virtual Desktop Infrastructure (VDI)
\begin{itemize}
\item Can connect to as pre-built desktop
\item Can access from any OS
\item All information / data local to virtual desktop
\item Which keeps your personal device isolated and secure
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}


\section*{4.2 – Given a scenario, set up and configure client-side virtualization.}
\label{sec:org7d2c217}
\subsection*{What is a Virtual Machine (VM)?}
\label{sec:org62bb365}
\begin{itemize}
\item First of all, cool as heck
\begin{itemize}
\item It is a software-derived computer, but all virtual
\item This includes the CPU, RAM, accessories
\item And it lives inside whatever actual, real-world computer is hosting it
\end{itemize}
\item In the past, only one operating system could tun on one computer
\begin{itemize}
\item Now, the number of individual machines and OSs that can run on one computer are limited only by:
\begin{itemize}
\item The power of the CPU
\item The amount of RAM
\end{itemize}
\item CPU cycles and RAM must be shared between host and VM
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Purpose of virtual machines}
\label{sec:org4d6c026}
\begin{itemize}
\item An example to visualize:
\begin{itemize}
\item One powerful server which can run many virtual machines
\item Each virtual machine runs an operating system and some applications
\item Different users can log into the virtual machines and access their own stuff
\item Virtual machines are what make cloud computing work!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Resource requirements}
\label{sec:orga0e5888}
\begin{itemize}
\item CPU processor support:
\begin{itemize}
\item Intel and AMD have their own virtualization technologies:
\begin{itemize}
\item Intel: Virtualization Technology (VT)
\item AMD: AMD-V
\item Your CPU must support virtualization
\end{itemize}
\item Memory: must have enough to run your own CPU and your guest CPU
\item Disk space - the guest machine will need its own space
\begin{itemize}
\item It's a little like having a messy, demanding, entitled roommate
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Hypervisor}
\label{sec:org38ca225}
\begin{itemize}
\item The main part of virtual machine structure
\begin{itemize}
\item A piece of software which allows multiple operating systems to share the same host
\item Also known as a Virtual Machine Manager (VMM)
\end{itemize}
\item Hypervisors make the whole thing possible
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Types of hypervisors}
\label{sec:org5486389}
\begin{itemize}
\item Type 1 Hypervisor
\begin{itemize}
\item Sits directly on the hardware of the host machine
\item For this reason also known as a \emph{bare metal hypervisor}
\item Generally faster, more efficient
\item Most commonly used for server-side virtualization
\begin{itemize}
\item (rather than what you might do on your personal machine)
\item Because it has few hardware requirements \emph{for itself}
\item Examples include:
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows-server/virtualization/hyper-v/hyper-v-technology-overview}{Microsoft Hyper-V}
\item \href{https://www.vmware.com/products/esxi-and-esx.html}{VMware ESXi}
\item an open source hypervisor: \href{https://www.linux-kvm.org/page/Main\_Page}{Linux KVM}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\item Type 2 hypervisor
\begin{itemize}
\item Sits on top of an existing operating system
\item Software to run virtual machines
\item More likely to be the kind of thing you use
\begin{itemize}
\item (which you should!)
\end{itemize}
\item Examples include:
\begin{itemize}
\item \href{https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/958559/description-of-windows-virtual-pc}{Windows Virtual PC} - older, ran on Windows 7!
\item \href{https://www.vmware.com/products/workstation-pro/workstation-pro-evaluation.html}{VMware Workstation}
\item And of course a free open source Type 2 hypervisor: \href{https://www.virtualbox.org/}{Oracle VirtualBox}
\begin{itemize}
\item This is what I used in class on my own machine to show you some things
\item Try it out!
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{An example of a Type 2 hypervisor running}
\label{sec:org4eeb5cf}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.75\textwidth]{./images/4-2-VBoxUbuntuMateMyMachine.png}
\captionof{figure}{Ubuntu Mate 18.04 running on a MacBook (Catalina)}
\end{center}

\subsection*{Emulator requirements}
\label{sec:org10df006}
\begin{itemize}
\item Emulators are different from VMs
\item Running original code to run on a different machine
\begin{itemize}
\item i.e. running a Windows 7 program on a Mac
\item Difficult, often much slower and almost unmanageable
\item The shortcomings of emulation is why VMs exist
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Security requirements}
\label{sec:org74b7642}
\begin{itemize}
\item No VM vulnerabilities yet, but boy this has potential
\begin{itemize}
\item Imagine the VM escaping into its host
\item Could conceivable infect other VMs
\item Each VM needs to run its own firewall and antiviral anti-malware solution
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{Network requirements}
\label{sec:org321dff1}
\begin{itemize}
\item Client-side VMs have their own virtual (internal) networks
\item \textbf{Shared network address}
\begin{itemize}
\item Each guest VM uses a private internal IP
\item And uses the guest IP through NAT \hyperref[sec:org24873f5]{see earlier slide}
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Bridged network address}
\begin{itemize}
\item The VM exists as a device on the physical network (LAN)
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Private network address}
\begin{itemize}
\item The VM cannot communicate outside its host
\item (this is the most secure route, but not as useful)
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\section*{5.1 – Given a scenario, use the best practice methodology to resolve problems.}
\label{sec:org120ed4f}

\subsection*{Step 0: Think about the context}
\label{sec:orgf627ffe}

Always consider corporate policies, procedures, and impacts before implementing changes

\subsection*{1. Identify the problem}
\label{sec:orgd49deb8}
\begin{itemize}
\item Question the user and identify user changes to computer and perform backups before making
changes
\item Inquire regarding environmental or infrastructure changes
\item Review system and application logs
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{2. Establish a theory of probable cause (question the obvious)}
\label{sec:org17a23c5}

\begin{itemize}
\item If necessary, conduct external or internal research based on symptoms
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{3. Test the theory to determine cause}
\label{sec:orgbce3712}

\begin{itemize}
\item Once the theory is confirmed, determine the next steps to resolve problem
\item If theory is not confirmed, establish new theory or escalate
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{4. Establish a plan of action to resolve the problem and implement the solution}
\label{sec:org135654a}
\begin{itemize}
\item Build the plan
\begin{itemize}
\item Calculate and document impact of solution
\item Backup / backout if things go bad
\end{itemize}
\item Fix it!
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{5. Verify full system functionality and, if applicable, implement preventive measures}
\label{sec:orgea77806}
\begin{itemize}
\item Restart the machine
\item Confirm the fix
\item Discuss with user
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{6. Document findings, actions, and outcomes}
\label{sec:orgfc213de}
\begin{itemize}
\item Contribute to knowledge base
\item Useful if problem occurs again
\item In a legal sense, didn't happen until you document it
\end{itemize}
\subsection*{A flowchart}
\label{sec:org115280b}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./images/5-1-HowToTroubleshootDiagram.png}
\captionof{figure}{Troubleshooting flowchart}
\end{center}
\end{document}
